Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.58,0:00:24.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Hi, everyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.49,0:00:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Good afternoon and welcome to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.38,0:00:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,this year's edition of what the
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.30,0:00:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,heck have those HLS folks been
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.82,0:00:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,up to lately.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.54,0:00:34.93,Default,,0,0,0,,It wouldn't fit on the slide
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.93,0:00:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,though so you kind of get what
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.46,0:00:37.98,Default,,0,0,0,,you get.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.98,0:00:39.16,Default,,0,0,0,,My name is Roger Pantos.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.16,0:00:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to be your host here
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.81,0:00:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,tonight and we have a bunch of
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.31,0:00:44.30,Default,,0,0,0,,stuff to talk about.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.62,0:00:46.92,Default,,0,0,0,,We have some new CODECS that are
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.92,0:00:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting, we have some new
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.46,0:00:50.93,Default,,0,0,0,,streaming features, and we have
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.93,0:00:53.25,Default,,0,0,0,,some enhancements to our APIs.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.99,0:00:57.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But first, we have our own
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.30,0:00:58.28,Default,,0,0,0,,announcement to make.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.81,0:01:01.44,Default,,0,0,0,,I am happy to announce that the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.44,0:01:05.37,Default,,0,0,0,,IETF has approved the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.37,0:01:08.04,Default,,0,0,0,,publication of the HLS spec as
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.04,0:01:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,an Internet draft.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.52,0:01:14.26,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.76,0:01:16.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So what this means is that the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.83,0:01:19.33,Default,,0,0,0,,current draft that's published
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.33,0:01:22.09,Default,,0,0,0,,on the site now, which is -23,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.36,0:01:23.79,Default,,0,0,0,,will move through the IETF
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.79,0:01:25.56,Default,,0,0,0,,publication process and once it
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.56,0:01:27.56,Default,,0,0,0,,does then it will be assigned an
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.56,0:01:28.28,Default,,0,0,0,,RFC number.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.07,0:01:31.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we've been sort of
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.80,0:01:33.37,Default,,0,0,0,,refreshing the draft for like 8
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.37,0:01:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,or 9 years now and there's a bit
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.10,0:01:37.49,Default,,0,0,0,,of question, okay, well why now?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.49,0:01:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Why publish an RFC?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.33,0:01:40.98,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the reasons is that we
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.98,0:01:42.50,Default,,0,0,0,,have heard feedback from some
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.50,0:01:44.73,Default,,0,0,0,,people that it's a little scary
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.73,0:01:46.28,Default,,0,0,0,,to be writing to a spec that's
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.28,0:01:47.93,Default,,0,0,0,,sort of continuously in draft
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.93,0:01:48.22,Default,,0,0,0,,mode.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.69,0:01:49.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And we get that.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.77,0:01:51.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We understand it.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.02,0:01:54.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And so publishing the spec as an
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.02,0:01:56.67,Default,,0,0,0,,RFC will allow it to serve as a
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.67,0:01:59.64,Default,,0,0,0,,stable reference going forward,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.98,0:02:01.85,Default,,0,0,0,,which means that you'll be able
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.85,0:02:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to build on it with confidence,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.74,0:02:05.21,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll be able to cite it in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.21,0:02:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,other specifications, and we
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.30,0:02:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,hope it will help improve things
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.20,0:02:12.03,Default,,0,0,0,,a little bit in some areas of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.03,0:02:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the industry.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.50,0:02:15.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, are we going to stop
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.15,0:02:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,improving HLS?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.59,0:02:18.51,Default,,0,0,0,,No, of course not.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.51,0:02:20.61,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to continue to
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.33,0:02:22.50,Default,,0,0,0,,evolve it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.92,0:02:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And we're going to make it
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.88,0:02:28.13,Default,,0,0,0,,better and better for the user's
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.13,0:02:30.03,Default,,0,0,0,,streaming experience, starting
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.03,0:02:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,with the things we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.77,0:02:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,be talking about today.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.19,0:02:33.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And so the way we're going to do
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.65,0:02:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,that is we're going to introduce
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.94,0:02:38.17,Default,,0,0,0,,a new internet draft that will
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.31,0:02:40.08,Default,,0,0,0,,build upon the coming RFC as a
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.08,0:02:42.43,Default,,0,0,0,,baseline and so keep an eye out
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.34,0:02:44.21,Default,,0,0,0,,for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.21,0:02:45.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. Now, let's move to the
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.54,0:02:46.99,Default,,0,0,0,,other big news of the conference
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.11,0:02:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,which is HEVC.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.45,0:02:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,As you heard at the keynotes and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.95,0:02:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,elsewhere, Apple has chosen HEVC
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.70,0:02:55.17,Default,,0,0,0,,as our next generation video
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.17,0:02:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,CODEC.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.33,0:02:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, why did we do it?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.39,0:02:59.77,Default,,0,0,0,,In one word, efficiency.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.31,0:03:02.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And primarily, encoding
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.21,0:03:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,efficiency.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.57,0:03:09.29,Default,,0,0,0,,HEVC is around abouts 40% more
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.29,0:03:10.39,Default,,0,0,0,,efficient than AVC.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.39,0:03:11.81,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, it depends on your
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.81,0:03:13.09,Default,,0,0,0,,content and it depends how good
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.09,0:03:14.81,Default,,0,0,0,,your encoder is, but 40% is a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.81,0:03:16.19,Default,,0,0,0,,nice ballpark figure.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.97,0:03:18.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And for those of us who spend
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.69,0:03:20.04,Default,,0,0,0,,our time schlepping media over
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.04,0:03:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,network that's exciting because
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.33,0:03:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,first of all it means that your
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.00,0:03:26.83,Default,,0,0,0,,user is going to see startup at
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.83,0:03:29.28,Default,,0,0,0,,a decent quality 40% faster, and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.28,0:03:30.64,Default,,0,0,0,,when the player adapts its way
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.64,0:03:32.04,Default,,0,0,0,,all the way up they'll see
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.04,0:03:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,content that looks 40% better.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.99,0:03:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And so that's an important thing
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.79,0:03:38.28,Default,,0,0,0,,for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.51,0:03:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,So HEVC is good.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.14,0:03:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Where can you get it?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.14,0:03:44.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Well as we've said, we are
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.33,0:03:46.18,Default,,0,0,0,,making HEVC widely available.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.38,0:03:47.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And in fact, on our newest
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.90,0:03:49.84,Default,,0,0,0,,devices, our newest iOS devices
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.84,0:03:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,with A9 and later and our latest
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.59,0:03:54.68,Default,,0,0,0,,generation of Macintoshes, we
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.68,0:03:56.44,Default,,0,0,0,,have support for HEVC built into
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.44,0:03:57.87,Default,,0,0,0,,the hardware and so that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.87,0:03:59.49,Default,,0,0,0,,includes support for FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.49,0:03:59.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.47,0:04:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Even on devices, on older
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.91,0:04:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,devices that don't have that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.27,0:04:07.31,Default,,0,0,0,,hardware support, we are still
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.31,0:04:09.80,Default,,0,0,0,,going to deploy a software HEVC
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.80,0:04:10.37,Default,,0,0,0,,CODEC.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.75,0:04:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And so that will be on all the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.28,0:04:14.36,Default,,0,0,0,,iOS devices receiving, iOS 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.63,0:04:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,That will include the Apple TV
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.16,0:04:19.25,Default,,0,0,0,,with tvOS 11 and Macintoshes
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.47,0:04:21.98,Default,,0,0,0,,that are upgraded to High
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.98,0:04:22.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Sierra.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.22,0:04:26.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So, HEVC is going to be a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.14,0:04:26.93,Default,,0,0,0,,different places.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.22,0:04:29.48,Default,,0,0,0,,We'd like you to use it.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.48,0:04:32.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And to use it with HLS there are
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.23,0:04:33.38,Default,,0,0,0,,a few things you need to keep in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.38,0:04:33.74,Default,,0,0,0,,mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.36,0:04:36.81,Default,,0,0,0,,The first is that HEVC
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.81,0:04:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,represents an entirely brand new
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.74,0:04:42.18,Default,,0,0,0,,encode of your content for a lot
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.18,0:04:44.64,Default,,0,0,0,,of people, and that means on the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.64,0:04:45.55,Default,,0,0,0,,bright side there's no
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.55,0:04:47.22,Default,,0,0,0,,compatibility version -- burden,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.22,0:04:47.53,Default,,0,0,0,,rather.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.98,0:04:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And so we decided that it was a
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.95,0:04:53.56,Default,,0,0,0,,good time to refocus our
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.56,0:04:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,attention on a single container
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.29,0:04:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,format and we looked at the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.82,0:04:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,alternatives and we decided that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.14,0:05:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,fragmented MPEG-4 had the most
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.30,0:05:02.55,Default,,0,0,0,,legs going forward.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.79,0:05:04.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So that means if you're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.60,0:05:07.73,Default,,0,0,0,,deploy your HEVC content to HLS,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.04,0:05:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,it has to be packaged as MP4
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.75,0:05:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,fragments.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.52,0:05:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.66,0:05:19.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, another nice thing there is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.02,0:05:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,that it makes the encoding story
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.95,0:05:23.86,Default,,0,0,0,,or rather the encryption story a
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.86,0:05:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit simpler because our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.20,0:05:29.86,Default,,0,0,0,,old buddy common encryption in
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.86,0:05:32.12,Default,,0,0,0,,cbcs mode works the same way
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.12,0:05:34.96,Default,,0,0,0,,with HEVC as it does with H.264.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.25,0:05:36.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And so there are no new rules
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.31,0:05:37.33,Default,,0,0,0,,there, you just have to do the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.33,0:05:39.37,Default,,0,0,0,,same sort of thing you do to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.95,0:05:43.39,Default,,0,0,0,,your HEVC bit streams.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.51,0:05:46.27,Default,,0,0,0,,As with any new CODEC, you're
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.27,0:05:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,going to be deploying it to an
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.76,0:05:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,ecosystem where some devices
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.44,0:05:51.66,Default,,0,0,0,,can't speak HEVC and so it is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.66,0:05:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,critically important that you
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.75,0:05:55.92,Default,,0,0,0,,mark your bit streams as HEVC so
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.92,0:05:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,the devices that don't
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.78,0:05:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,understand it can steer around
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.46,0:05:59.55,Default,,0,0,0,,it.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.55,0:06:01.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And the way to do that, of
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.33,0:06:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,course in HLS, is with the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.52,0:06:03.96,Default,,0,0,0,,CODECS attribute in your master
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.96,0:06:04.58,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.64,0:06:07.59,Default,,0,0,0,,I've got an example here of a
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.82,0:06:09.30,Default,,0,0,0,,CODECS attribute for HEVC.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.30,0:06:10.57,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a little bit more
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.57,0:06:12.30,Default,,0,0,0,,complicated than H.264 but it's
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.30,0:06:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,not -- it's got a few more
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.39,0:06:15.49,Default,,0,0,0,,things in it but it's not too
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.49,0:06:15.58,Default,,0,0,0,,bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.58,0:06:17.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And the entire format is
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.76,0:06:21.46,Default,,0,0,0,,documented in the HEVC spec. So
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.46,0:06:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,speaking of older clients in
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.79,0:06:25.22,Default,,0,0,0,,H.264, there is naturally kind
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.22,0:06:26.59,Default,,0,0,0,,of a compatibility question
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.59,0:06:29.55,Default,,0,0,0,,around here of, first of all,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.55,0:06:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,can you deploy a single asset to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.44,0:06:35.47,Default,,0,0,0,,both older and new clients?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.61,0:06:36.84,Default,,0,0,0,,And the answer is yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.00,0:06:42.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.64,0:06:45.90,Default,,0,0,0,,You can mix HEVC and H.264
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.90,0:06:47.56,Default,,0,0,0,,variants in the same master
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.56,0:06:49.61,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist, and that goes for both
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.61,0:06:51.59,Default,,0,0,0,,the regular video variance and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.59,0:06:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,also the I-frame variance.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.76,0:06:54.61,Default,,0,0,0,,You can have HEVC and H.264
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.61,0:06:55.91,Default,,0,0,0,,versions of those as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.65,0:06:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,As I said, you do need to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.09,0:07:01.18,Default,,0,0,0,,package your HEVC in MPEG-4
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.18,0:07:02.78,Default,,0,0,0,,fragments, but for backward
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.78,0:07:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,compatibility H.264 can either
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.77,0:07:07.33,Default,,0,0,0,,be in transforce frames or in
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.33,0:07:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,fragmented MPEG-4, your choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.77,0:07:11.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, it becomes even more
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.57,0:07:12.61,Default,,0,0,0,,critically important that you
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.61,0:07:14.89,Default,,0,0,0,,label your media playlist so
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.89,0:07:17.31,Default,,0,0,0,,that we know what is what.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.74,0:07:20.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And finally, we have actually
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.71,0:07:22.23,Default,,0,0,0,,updated -- we have -- if
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.23,0:07:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,you-guys don't know, we have a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.76,0:07:24.97,Default,,0,0,0,,document called the HLS
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.97,0:07:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Authoring guidelines, Best
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.27,0:07:29.08,Default,,0,0,0,,practices for Apple TV and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.08,0:07:30.02,Default,,0,0,0,,stuff.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.02,0:07:31.41,Default,,0,0,0,,I think we changed the name.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.80,0:07:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But anyway, it doesn't matter
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.15,0:07:35.29,Default,,0,0,0,,because there's actually a video
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.29,0:07:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,on demand talk that's available
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.68,0:07:38.99,Default,,0,0,0,,today called the HLS Authoring
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.99,0:07:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Update, and we've updated that
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.48,0:07:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,for HEVC.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.32,0:07:44.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And so the Authoring guide now
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.66,0:07:46.04,Default,,0,0,0,,has some additional
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.04,0:07:48.22,Default,,0,0,0,,considerations for HEVC as well
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.22,0:07:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,as sort of a initial set of
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.89,0:07:52.35,Default,,0,0,0,,recommended bit-rate tiers to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.35,0:07:53.44,Default,,0,0,0,,get you-guys going on that.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.44,0:07:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So check out that talk.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.34,0:07:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,I hear the guy giving it is
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.75,0:07:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,awesome.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.61,0:08:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, we've got a new subtitle
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.62,0:08:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,format, and this is called IMSC.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.10,0:08:10.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now many of you will not have
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.19,0:08:11.13,Default,,0,0,0,,heard of IMSC.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.13,0:08:14.49,Default,,0,0,0,,In the consumer space it's not
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:17.47,Default,,0,0,0,,quite as big as VTT is yet, but
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.21,0:08:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,it is sort of a grandchild of a
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.54,0:08:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,more well-known format called
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.00,0:08:25.27,Default,,0,0,0,,the Timed Text Markup Language
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.27,0:08:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,or TTML.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.49,0:08:29.45,Default,,0,0,0,,TTML is kind of a extremely
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.45,0:08:31.39,Default,,0,0,0,,expressive, not particularly
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.39,0:08:33.72,Default,,0,0,0,,lightweight authoring language,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.72,0:08:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,primarily, for subtitles and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.06,0:08:37.41,Default,,0,0,0,,captions and it's used for
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.41,0:08:39.51,Default,,0,0,0,,mezzanines and interchange and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.51,0:08:40.91,Default,,0,0,0,,that kind of thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.91,0:08:41.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And so what the Timed Text
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.91,0:08:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,working group did was they took
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.44,0:08:47.21,Default,,0,0,0,,TTML and they kind of slimed it
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.21,0:08:48.35,Default,,0,0,0,,down, streamlined it a little
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.35,0:08:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,bit for delivery of regular
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.28,0:08:51.76,Default,,0,0,0,,captions to consumers over the
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.76,0:08:52.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Internet.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.54,0:08:54.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And so that is called IMSC.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.76,0:08:58.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we already do VTT and so it
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.70,0:08:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,brings the obvious question of
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.81,0:09:01.45,Default,,0,0,0,,well why is IMSC different?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.86,0:09:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And the primary difference is
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.70,0:09:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that IMSC has much better
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.44,0:09:09.22,Default,,0,0,0,,support, much more extensive
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.22,0:09:11.71,Default,,0,0,0,,styling controls than VTT does.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.71,0:09:13.64,Default,,0,0,0,,VTT kind of has a few basic
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.64,0:09:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,styling controls and then for
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.71,0:09:18.35,Default,,0,0,0,,the rest of it leans on CSS.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.35,0:09:19.45,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC has a much more
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.45,0:09:21.79,Default,,0,0,0,,self-contained set of styling
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.79,0:09:24.58,Default,,0,0,0,,features that are focused on the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.58,0:09:26.35,Default,,0,0,0,,kind of stylings you need to do
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.35,0:09:28.12,Default,,0,0,0,,for subtitles and captions.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.79,0:09:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And so it's gotten a certain
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.02,0:09:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,amount of traction, particularly
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.50,0:09:34.90,Default,,0,0,0,,in the broadcasting industry,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.52,0:09:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,and so much so that it was
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.39,0:09:40.95,Default,,0,0,0,,chosen last year as the baseline
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.95,0:09:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,format for MPEG's common media
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.90,0:09:45.24,Default,,0,0,0,,application format that we told
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.24,0:09:46.02,Default,,0,0,0,,you about last year.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.02,0:09:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And so what we're doing in iOS
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.46,0:09:50.91,Default,,0,0,0,,11 and the other various
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.91,0:09:54.04,Default,,0,0,0,,releases is we are rolling out a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.04,0:09:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,first generation ground-up
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.69,0:10:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,implementation of IMSC and so
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.19,0:10:02.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that's in your seat today, and
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.41,0:10:04.85,Default,,0,0,0,,we expect to refine it going
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.85,0:10:05.26,Default,,0,0,0,,forward.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.01,0:10:10.16,Default,,0,0,0,,So just as with HEVC, there are
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.16,0:10:11.19,Default,,0,0,0,,a few things you need to know
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.19,0:10:12.48,Default,,0,0,0,,about IMSC in order to use it
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.48,0:10:13.22,Default,,0,0,0,,with HLS.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.52,0:10:14.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The first thing is how it's
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.52,0:10:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,packaged.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.50,0:10:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Unlike VTT, which the segments
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.60,0:10:18.84,Default,,0,0,0,,-- where the segments are just
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.84,0:10:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,little text files, the carriage
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.27,0:10:23.30,Default,,0,0,0,,of IMSC is defined by MPEG-4,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.30,0:10:25.99,Default,,0,0,0,,part 30 and it basically what it
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.99,0:10:28.11,Default,,0,0,0,,comes down to is XML text inside
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.11,0:10:30.04,Default,,0,0,0,,of MPEG-4 fragments, and so it
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.04,0:10:31.49,Default,,0,0,0,,takes advantage of all the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.94,0:10:33.43,Default,,0,0,0,,MPEG-4 timing facilities.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.01,0:10:35.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And I say text because IMSC
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.87,0:10:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,actually defines 2 profiles, an
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.55,0:10:39.79,Default,,0,0,0,,image profile and a text
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.79,0:10:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,profile.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.60,0:10:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Our client only supports the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.31,0:10:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,text profile of IMSC, and so
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.37,0:10:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,when you label your playlist,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.59,0:10:51.10,Default,,0,0,0,,which you should do because you
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.10,0:10:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,face the same issue with old
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.82,0:10:54.27,Default,,0,0,0,,clients not understanding IMSC,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.27,0:10:57.12,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll want to add the CODECS
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.12,0:10:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,tag for IMSC, and I've included
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.68,0:11:01.48,Default,,0,0,0,,a sample here which is
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.52,0:11:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,stpp.TTML.im1t, and that
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.59,0:11:06.15,Default,,0,0,0,,essentially says I have
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.15,0:11:07.58,Default,,0,0,0,,subtitles in my playlist that
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.58,0:11:10.65,Default,,0,0,0,,conform to the text profile of
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.65,0:11:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC1.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.49,0:11:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I've been talking about
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.70,0:11:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC and HEVC sort of in the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.33,0:11:17.80,Default,,0,0,0,,same breath.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.80,0:11:20.13,Default,,0,0,0,,I just want to sort of emphasize
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.13,0:11:21.50,Default,,0,0,0,,that they're not linked.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.82,0:11:22.86,Default,,0,0,0,,You can use them independently.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.86,0:11:23.66,Default,,0,0,0,,You can use HEVC with VTT.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.66,0:11:27.37,Default,,0,0,0,,You can use IMSC with H.264.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.37,0:11:28.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You can use them all together,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.81,0:11:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and you can actually even have a
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.83,0:11:34.02,Default,,0,0,0,,single playlist that has VTT and
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.02,0:11:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC so that newer clients can
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.06,0:11:37.91,Default,,0,0,0,,get the benefits of IMSC styling
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.08,0:11:40.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and older clients can continue
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.26,0:11:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,to use VTT.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.11,0:11:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And so let's take a look at a
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.00,0:11:43.03,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist and show you what that
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.03,0:11:43.49,Default,,0,0,0,,looks like.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.29,0:11:45.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I've got a fragment of a master
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.52,0:11:47.98,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist here and that first set
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.98,0:11:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,of lines up there should be
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.59,0:11:50.64,Default,,0,0,0,,pretty familiar to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.64,0:11:51.80,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what your master playlist
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.80,0:11:53.25,Default,,0,0,0,,would look like if you had a
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.25,0:11:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,video variant called bipbop
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.44,0:11:57.95,Default,,0,0,0,,gear1 and it had VTT based
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.95,0:11:59.08,Default,,0,0,0,,subtitles in it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.53,0:12:02.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That next set of tags has the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.68,0:12:05.32,Default,,0,0,0,,same video tier but in its
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.32,0:12:07.38,Default,,0,0,0,,CODECS attribute you see it's
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.38,0:12:08.79,Default,,0,0,0,,labeled as IMSC.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.12,0:12:11.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And so the first one will pull
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.77,0:12:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,down the VTT.m3u8 playlist, the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.09,0:12:16.61,Default,,0,0,0,,second will pull down the IMSC
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.61,0:12:17.90,Default,,0,0,0,,if the client can understand
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.90,0:12:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,that.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.16,0:12:20.89,Default,,0,0,0,,If we sort of dive into those
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.89,0:12:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,two media playlists they're
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.13,0:12:23.17,Default,,0,0,0,,actually pretty similar.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.17,0:12:26.58,Default,,0,0,0,,You can see that the VTT is, you
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.82,0:12:28.01,Default,,0,0,0,,know, as you'd expect, just a
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.01,0:12:31.35,Default,,0,0,0,,list of .VTT segments and the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.35,0:12:33.43,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC is also sort of, in this
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.43,0:12:34.97,Default,,0,0,0,,case MP4 segments because there
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.97,0:12:36.82,Default,,0,0,0,,are MPEG-4 fragments and it does
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.82,0:12:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,have them tagged because that's
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.63,0:12:41.12,Default,,0,0,0,,what fragmented MPEG-4 requires
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.12,0:12:42.47,Default,,0,0,0,,is we need to be able to point
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.47,0:12:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,at the movie box.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.01,0:12:45.38,Default,,0,0,0,,So, but other than that they're
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.38,0:12:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,very similar.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.50,0:12:48.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So IMSC, VTT they're very
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.95,0:12:49.75,Default,,0,0,0,,similar.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.82,0:12:53.47,Default,,0,0,0,,They do the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.68,0:12:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Why would I switch my HLS
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.20,0:12:56.18,Default,,0,0,0,,streams for IMSC?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.47,0:12:58.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you might switch your
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.67,0:13:02.07,Default,,0,0,0,,streams if, first of all, if you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.07,0:13:04.45,Default,,0,0,0,,want more stylist to control and
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.45,0:13:06.67,Default,,0,0,0,,you don't have an entire CSS
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.82,0:13:08.96,Default,,0,0,0,,parser to lean on in your
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.96,0:13:11.40,Default,,0,0,0,,playback devices then IMSC can
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.40,0:13:12.04,Default,,0,0,0,,be attractive.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.34,0:13:16.08,Default,,0,0,0,,A second good reason is that you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.08,0:13:17.83,Default,,0,0,0,,may be authoring your captions
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.83,0:13:20.32,Default,,0,0,0,,already in TTML, or perhaps
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.32,0:13:21.06,Default,,0,0,0,,you're getting them from a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.06,0:13:23.15,Default,,0,0,0,,service provider in one of those
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.15,0:13:24.19,Default,,0,0,0,,formats.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.19,0:13:25.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And you may find that
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.61,0:13:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,translating TTML's IMSC is both
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.95,0:13:30.46,Default,,0,0,0,,simpler and perhaps higher
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.46,0:13:32.36,Default,,0,0,0,,fidelity than doing the same
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.36,0:13:34.20,Default,,0,0,0,,translation to VTT because
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.20,0:13:34.96,Default,,0,0,0,,they're much more similar
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.96,0:13:35.67,Default,,0,0,0,,formats.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.16,0:13:37.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So another good reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.52,0:13:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,And a final reason is that you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.42,0:13:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,may find yourself producing
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.87,0:13:43.54,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC1 streams anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.06,0:13:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We mentioned that CMAF is
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.03,0:13:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,requiring IMSC for captions in
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.75,0:13:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,CMAF presentations, and if you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.12,0:13:55.89,Default,,0,0,0,,find yourself wanting to take
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.89,0:13:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,advantage of the pool of
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.54,0:13:58.96,Default,,0,0,0,,compatible devices that we hope
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.96,0:14:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,CMAF will produce then you're
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.66,0:14:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,going to end up with IMSC1
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.00,0:14:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,streams and you may be able to
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.30,0:14:11.69,Default,,0,0,0,,just drop the VTT streams and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.69,0:14:12.94,Default,,0,0,0,,that would simplify your tool
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.94,0:14:13.93,Default,,0,0,0,,chain and your production
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.93,0:14:14.30,Default,,0,0,0,,workflow.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.71,0:14:20.45,Default,,0,0,0,,So now having said all of that,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.75,0:14:21.85,Default,,0,0,0,,maybe none of that applies to
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.85,0:14:24.77,Default,,0,0,0,,you in which case sticking with
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.77,0:14:26.10,Default,,0,0,0,,VTT is a fine choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.10,0:14:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,It's going to continue being
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.21,0:14:27.42,Default,,0,0,0,,around.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.42,0:14:29.72,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, maybe you're mainly
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.72,0:14:31.11,Default,,0,0,0,,focused on North American market
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.11,0:14:33.25,Default,,0,0,0,,in which case 608 is fine too.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.31,0:14:34.23,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not going anywhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.72,0:14:35.97,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we've just got different
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.97,0:14:36.45,Default,,0,0,0,,choices.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.60,0:14:39.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I've been talking a lot
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.47,0:14:40.67,Default,,0,0,0,,about IMSC1.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.67,0:14:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,There might be a question
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.78,0:14:43.16,Default,,0,0,0,,lingering as to well is there an
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.47,0:14:44.41,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC2?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.44,0:14:47.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And the answer is kind of.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.53,0:14:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It hasn't been finalized yet, in
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.14,0:14:50.17,Default,,0,0,0,,fact it's still working through
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.17,0:14:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,its process but the Time Text
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.07,0:14:55.09,Default,,0,0,0,,working group is planning on
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.09,0:14:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,defining an IMSC2, and one of
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.73,0:14:58.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the features in it that we're
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.81,0:15:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,keeping an eye on is some more
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.79,0:15:03.37,Default,,0,0,0,,silent controls that are
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.37,0:15:05.32,Default,,0,0,0,,particularly aimed at some
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.32,0:15:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,advanced Japanese topography
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.21,0:15:09.84,Default,,0,0,0,,features such as shatti and
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.84,0:15:10.63,Default,,0,0,0,,ticochiyoko [phonetically
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.63,0:15:11.10,Default,,0,0,0,,spelled].
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.10,0:15:16.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And so the short story is that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.14,0:15:18.72,Default,,0,0,0,,IMSC2, we expect the story to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.72,0:15:19.94,Default,,0,0,0,,evolve over the next couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.94,0:15:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,years and so keep an eye out for
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.32,0:15:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.53,0:15:24.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So that's our CODECS
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.94,0:15:26.75,Default,,0,0,0,,story, now let's talk about some
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.75,0:15:27.50,Default,,0,0,0,,streaming features.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.82,0:15:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And first I'd like to talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.82,0:15:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,something that we have that we
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.79,0:15:34.59,Default,,0,0,0,,hope will make the lives of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.59,0:15:36.14,Default,,0,0,0,,those longsuffering produces of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.14,0:15:37.83,Default,,0,0,0,,live streams a little bit easier
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.24,0:15:40.30,Default,,0,0,0,,in terms of helping them
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.30,0:15:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,maintain a robust experience
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.53,0:15:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,because HLS players are usually
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.00,0:15:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,pretty good when everything
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.88,0:15:48.11,Default,,0,0,0,,going on in the back end is kind
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.11,0:15:50.50,Default,,0,0,0,,of running tickety-boo, but when
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.50,0:15:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,things start to fall over on the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.90,0:15:52.92,Default,,0,0,0,,back end the clients could
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.92,0:15:54.26,Default,,0,0,0,,actually do a little bit better
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.64,0:15:55.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to help things move along.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.58,0:15:56.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me show you what I mean.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.30,0:16:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So here we have -- I guess here
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.54,0:16:03.99,Default,,0,0,0,,we have a -- your typical live
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.99,0:16:04.85,Default,,0,0,0,,HLS playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.85,0:16:05.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Got a ten-second target
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.74,0:16:07.20,Default,,0,0,0,,duration, segments are you now
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.20,0:16:09.01,Default,,0,0,0,,10 seconds or thereabouts, after
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.01,0:16:10.14,Default,,0,0,0,,10 seconds you might want to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.14,0:16:10.62,Default,,0,0,0,,reload it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.03,0:16:12.61,Default,,0,0,0,,File sequence 12 is at the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.61,0:16:14.36,Default,,0,0,0,,bottom there, but oh now file
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.36,0:16:15.43,Default,,0,0,0,,sequence 13 appears.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.81,0:16:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,10 seconds later you reload
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.06,0:16:18.94,Default,,0,0,0,,again, file sequence 14 appears.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.27,0:16:20.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Those things aren't appearing by
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.76,0:16:21.70,Default,,0,0,0,,magic, of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.93,0:16:23.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You've got some encoder worker
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.26,0:16:24.29,Default,,0,0,0,,somewhere that's chewing on a
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.29,0:16:25.83,Default,,0,0,0,,media source, and every 10
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.83,0:16:26.84,Default,,0,0,0,,seconds it's writing on a new
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.84,0:16:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,segment file into the CEN.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.92,0:16:33.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What would happen if for
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.88,0:16:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,whatever reason the encoder
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.10,0:16:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,suddenly rebooted?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.19,0:16:37.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Or maybe you knock your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.84,0:16:38.91,Default,,0,0,0,,microwave dish with your elbow
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.91,0:16:39.79,Default,,0,0,0,,or something, you lose your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.79,0:16:41.25,Default,,0,0,0,,media feed.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.25,0:16:45.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, prior to this HLS clients
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.12,0:16:46.98,Default,,0,0,0,,had no way of knowing that that
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.98,0:16:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,had happened and so they had no
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.14,0:16:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,way to help out.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.44,0:16:51.69,Default,,0,0,0,,But now we defined a new tag
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.92,0:16:54.49,Default,,0,0,0,,which is called the GAP tag, and
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.49,0:16:55.95,Default,,0,0,0,,so now what you can do instead
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.95,0:16:57.77,Default,,0,0,0,,on your back end is when you
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.77,0:17:00.30,Default,,0,0,0,,lose your encoder or you lose
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.30,0:17:02.11,Default,,0,0,0,,your media source your packager
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.41,0:17:04.17,Default,,0,0,0,,can continue writing segments
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.58,0:17:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,but instead of writing the media
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.75,0:17:09.23,Default,,0,0,0,,data it can simply write a dummy
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.23,0:17:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,URL and affix that with a GAP
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.88,0:17:12.30,Default,,0,0,0,,tag.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.90,0:17:14.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And it can continue doing this
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.79,0:17:17.22,Default,,0,0,0,,as long as the encoding for that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.22,0:17:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,stream is disabled.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.13,0:17:20.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And so 10 seconds later you
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.58,0:17:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,might get another segment that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.43,0:17:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,is indicated as a gap.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.18,0:17:25.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So this tells the player that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.48,0:17:27.78,Default,,0,0,0,,the stream is still alive, it's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.78,0:17:29.57,Default,,0,0,0,,still chugging along, it's still
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.57,0:17:32.47,Default,,0,0,0,,updating but things aren't so
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.47,0:17:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,good in actually media data
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.71,0:17:34.15,Default,,0,0,0,,land.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.83,0:17:36.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Once things are restored, once
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.93,0:17:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,your encoder comes back or your
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.45,0:17:40.20,Default,,0,0,0,,-- you've straightened out your
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.20,0:17:42.62,Default,,0,0,0,,microwave dish or what have you,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.62,0:17:44.36,Default,,0,0,0,,then the packager can continue
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.50,0:17:46.37,Default,,0,0,0,,producing segments as it did
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.37,0:17:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,before.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.09,0:17:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what does the GAP tag mean
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.32,0:17:50.24,Default,,0,0,0,,to you as a client?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.28,0:17:54.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Primarily it means that there's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.13,0:17:57.52,Default,,0,0,0,,no media data here and so of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.52,0:18:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,course as a first approximation
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.13,0:18:02.09,Default,,0,0,0,,the player shouldn't attempt to
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.09,0:18:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,download it because it's not
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.54,0:18:07.03,Default,,0,0,0,,there, but more interestingly as
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.03,0:18:08.71,Default,,0,0,0,,soon as the player sees a GAP
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.71,0:18:10.77,Default,,0,0,0,,tag appear in a media playlist
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.06,0:18:12.33,Default,,0,0,0,,it can go off and attempt to
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.33,0:18:13.89,Default,,0,0,0,,find another variant that
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.89,0:18:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn't have the same gaps
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.16,0:18:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,because you may have multiple
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.72,0:18:18.51,Default,,0,0,0,,redundant encoders producing
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.51,0:18:19.72,Default,,0,0,0,,different variants or redundant
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.72,0:18:21.43,Default,,0,0,0,,variants, and so maybe we're
Dialogue: 0,0:18:21.43,0:18:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,playing the 2-megabit stream and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.44,0:18:24.75,Default,,0,0,0,,we might find that when we find
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.78,0:18:26.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the 1-megabit stream that oh,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.50,0:18:27.69,Default,,0,0,0,,actually he doesn't have a gap
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.94,0:18:29.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and so we can just cleanly
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.10,0:18:30.64,Default,,0,0,0,,switch down to it, we can play
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.64,0:18:31.87,Default,,0,0,0,,through the 1-megabit stream.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.21,0:18:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Once we're done with the gap we
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.90,0:18:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,can switch back up to the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.09,0:18:36.33,Default,,0,0,0,,3-megabit stream, the 2-megabit
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.33,0:18:38.42,Default,,0,0,0,,stream, and it's all good.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.56,0:18:39.69,Default,,0,0,0,,The user won't even notice.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.28,0:18:47.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we have a fallback case
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.34,0:18:49.47,Default,,0,0,0,,which is that you might just
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.47,0:18:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,have one encoder, or like I said
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.07,0:18:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,you might have knocked out your
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.93,0:18:53.41,Default,,0,0,0,,media source, you may have no
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.41,0:18:55.23,Default,,0,0,0,,media for the entire gap, and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.32,0:18:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,the behavior of our player in
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.58,0:18:58.47,Default,,0,0,0,,that case is we'll just in a
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.47,0:18:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,live stream scenario continue to
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.96,0:19:01.72,Default,,0,0,0,,play through silence until media
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.72,0:19:02.87,Default,,0,0,0,,comes back and we can resume the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.87,0:19:03.49,Default,,0,0,0,,presentation.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.53,0:19:06.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the new GAP tag amongst
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.45,0:19:09.28,Default,,0,0,0,,other things is described in a
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.28,0:19:10.97,Default,,0,0,0,,version of the HLS beta spec
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.97,0:19:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,that I was up last night
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.06,0:19:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,writing, and so I think we're
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.95,0:19:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,posting it today, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.18,0:19:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,awesome.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.01,0:19:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't wait to see it.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.06,0:19:23.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.32,0:19:26.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Feedback of course is welcome.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.85,0:19:30.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's the GAP tag.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.13,0:19:31.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's talk about another new
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.03,0:19:32.14,Default,,0,0,0,,feature, and this is also kind
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.14,0:19:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,of aimed at your back-end folks.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.29,0:19:37.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And what we're doing is we are
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.24,0:19:38.98,Default,,0,0,0,,supporting simple variable
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.98,0:19:41.73,Default,,0,0,0,,substitution in m3u8 playlists,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.73,0:19:42.93,Default,,0,0,0,,and do to that we kind of
Dialogue: 0,0:19:42.93,0:19:44.98,Default,,0,0,0,,barrowed a little bit of syntax
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.98,0:19:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,from PHP.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.19,0:19:47.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And so what that means is if you
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.61,0:19:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,see something like that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.57,0:19:50.91,Default,,0,0,0,,highlighted bit in a playlist
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.91,0:19:52.77,Default,,0,0,0,,what it is saying is take that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.77,0:19:53.77,Default,,0,0,0,,thing that's surrounded by the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.77,0:19:55.31,Default,,0,0,0,,braces and replace it with the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.31,0:19:57.71,Default,,0,0,0,,value of the variable whose name
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.71,0:19:58.41,Default,,0,0,0,,is file name.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.70,0:20:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And so if the variable value
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.10,0:20:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,happens to be foo then you would
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.48,0:20:03.42,Default,,0,0,0,,end up with a string that is
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.42,0:20:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,foo.ts.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.90,0:20:10.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, to define these things we
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.02,0:20:12.27,Default,,0,0,0,,defined a new tag and it's
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.27,0:20:13.31,Default,,0,0,0,,pretty simple, I'll show it to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.31,0:20:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,you in a second, and it either
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.76,0:20:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,defines a variable inline the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.96,0:20:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist or it can import it.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.92,0:20:22.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, this is what makes things
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.60,0:20:23.93,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting because remember I
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.93,0:20:25.25,Default,,0,0,0,,said makes life a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.25,0:20:26.33,Default,,0,0,0,,better for people producing
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.33,0:20:26.65,Default,,0,0,0,,streams?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.65,0:20:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Well how does it do that?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.83,0:20:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, yeah, you could -- if
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.52,0:20:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,you've got big honking URL's you
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.68,0:20:33.33,Default,,0,0,0,,could use variables to make your
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.33,0:20:36.13,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist shorter but, I mean,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.13,0:20:36.99,Default,,0,0,0,,gsip [phonetic] already does a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.99,0:20:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,better job of that so that's not
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.70,0:20:40.85,Default,,0,0,0,,-- that's kind of -- but what's
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.96,0:20:42.75,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting is when you have the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.75,0:20:44.67,Default,,0,0,0,,ability to define a variable in
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.67,0:20:46.94,Default,,0,0,0,,a master playlist and make use
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.94,0:20:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,of it in a media playlist that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.88,0:20:50.44,Default,,0,0,0,,allows you to construct your
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.44,0:20:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,media playlists ahead of time
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.60,0:20:54.78,Default,,0,0,0,,with little placeholders that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:54.78,0:20:56.47,Default,,0,0,0,,are filled in sort of in a late
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.47,0:20:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,binding way when your master
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.32,0:20:59.40,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist is defined.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.40,0:21:01.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So for instance, you could have
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.18,0:21:03.07,Default,,0,0,0,,a bunch of variables references
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.07,0:21:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,in your media playlist on your
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.59,0:21:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,CDN and you could produce your
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.85,0:21:07.46,Default,,0,0,0,,master playlist dynamically from
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.46,0:21:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,your application and at that
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.32,0:21:11.25,Default,,0,0,0,,point you can say I want my
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.25,0:21:12.76,Default,,0,0,0,,variable to be this, and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.76,0:21:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,suddenly all your media
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.95,0:21:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,playlists on the CDN will take
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.12,0:21:16.27,Default,,0,0,0,,advantage of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.27,0:21:17.91,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's see what that looks
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.61,0:21:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,like.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.88,0:21:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Here's a master playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.47,0:21:21.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It's pretty simple example.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.78,0:21:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,So I've got a define tag here.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.16,0:21:25.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It has two attributes, the name
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.55,0:21:26.92,Default,,0,0,0,,attribute says the variable name
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.92,0:21:29.38,Default,,0,0,0,,is auth and it has a value which
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.38,0:21:31.03,Default,,0,0,0,,is this definition of an auth
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.03,0:21:31.37,Default,,0,0,0,,token.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.27,0:21:34.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And you can use this various
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.78,0:21:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,places in the master playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.18,0:21:38.53,Default,,0,0,0,,For instance, in my gear1 thing
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.53,0:21:41.08,Default,,0,0,0,,here I've decided to tack on the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.08,0:21:43.12,Default,,0,0,0,,auth token to the URL for the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.41,0:21:46.22,Default,,0,0,0,,first variant, but now let's
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.22,0:21:47.51,Default,,0,0,0,,imagine that we load that media
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.51,0:21:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.24,0:21:51.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, media playlists can have
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.32,0:21:52.41,Default,,0,0,0,,variables just like master
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.41,0:21:52.97,Default,,0,0,0,,playlists do.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.97,0:21:54.26,Default,,0,0,0,,In this case, I've got a path
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.54,0:21:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,that has this big long path.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.75,0:21:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't want to type a whole
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.52,0:21:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,bunch of different times.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.05,0:21:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,But the second define is a
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.11,0:21:59.97,Default,,0,0,0,,little more interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.27,0:22:02.18,Default,,0,0,0,,In this case, we're importing
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.34,0:22:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,that auth variable that we
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.62,0:22:05.09,Default,,0,0,0,,defined in the master playlist
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.25,0:22:06.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and we're applying it to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.09,0:22:08.41,Default,,0,0,0,,different places such as this
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.41,0:22:10.84,Default,,0,0,0,,URL in the media playlist, and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.84,0:22:14.64,Default,,0,0,0,,so this allows you to sort of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.74,0:22:16.43,Default,,0,0,0,,have a loose coupling effect
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.43,0:22:17.50,Default,,0,0,0,,between your master playlist and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.50,0:22:18.16,Default,,0,0,0,,your media playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.16,0:22:20.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I think that people are going to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.01,0:22:21.34,Default,,0,0,0,,find a lot of interesting uses
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.34,0:22:22.44,Default,,0,0,0,,for it.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.87,0:22:24.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.42,0:22:25.59,Default,,0,0,0,,So we talked about some back-end
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.59,0:22:26.01,Default,,0,0,0,,features.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.19,0:22:27.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's talk about something that
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.72,0:22:30.16,Default,,0,0,0,,you can actually use to provide
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.16,0:22:31.91,Default,,0,0,0,,a compelling user experience.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.33,0:22:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what do I mean?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.52,0:22:35.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Well for instance, what if you
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.23,0:22:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,wanted your users to be able to,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.16,0:22:39.34,Default,,0,0,0,,when they're watching a match,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.69,0:22:42.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to be watching one camera of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.50,0:22:43.39,Default,,0,0,0,,someone sort of crossing the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.39,0:22:44.75,Default,,0,0,0,,ball but at the same time
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.97,0:22:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,watching the goal keeper cameras
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.87,0:22:47.86,Default,,0,0,0,,so they could see his point of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.86,0:22:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,view as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.12,0:22:51.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Or what if you're watching a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.27,0:22:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,race and you want to see the car
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.12,0:22:56.89,Default,,0,0,0,,camera in Hamilton's car but you
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.89,0:22:58.27,Default,,0,0,0,,also want to keep an eye on
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.27,0:23:00.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Vettel behind him.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.21,0:23:04.60,Default,,0,0,0,,And so in that case what unites
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.60,0:23:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,these kind of features is the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.79,0:23:08.92,Default,,0,0,0,,ability to play multiple live
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.92,0:23:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,streams that are synchronized
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.69,0:23:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,with each other so that one
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.31,0:23:14.85,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn't get ahead of another.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.99,0:23:16.33,Default,,0,0,0,,[laughs] This is your future.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.00,0:23:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So in order to do that, all we
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.54,0:23:24.68,Default,,0,0,0,,require is that you have two or
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.68,0:23:26.78,Default,,0,0,0,,more live streams that are
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.88,0:23:30.13,Default,,0,0,0,,synchronized by the use of a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.13,0:23:30.71,Default,,0,0,0,,date-time tag.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.71,0:23:31.84,Default,,0,0,0,,That basically means you put
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.87,0:23:33.41,Default,,0,0,0,,dates in your playlist and the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.41,0:23:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,dates are both derived or are
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.60,0:23:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,derived in all the playlists
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.70,0:23:37.58,Default,,0,0,0,,from a common clock.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.07,0:23:39.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And once you've done that then
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.53,0:23:41.26,Default,,0,0,0,,you can create multiple
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.26,0:23:44.16,Default,,0,0,0,,independent AVPlayers and you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.16,0:23:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,can start the first one playing
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.70,0:23:46.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and then start the second one
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.83,0:23:49.17,Default,,0,0,0,,playing in sync by using the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.17,0:23:52.41,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPlayer setRatetime atHostTime
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.41,0:23:52.77,Default,,0,0,0,,method.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.25,0:23:55.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I should be up front here
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.21,0:23:58.45,Default,,0,0,0,,and say that using this method
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.45,0:24:00.23,Default,,0,0,0,,in AVPlayer gets you some
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.23,0:24:02.20,Default,,0,0,0,,serious AVFoundation street cred
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.55,0:24:04.11,Default,,0,0,0,,because it's not the simplest
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.11,0:24:04.97,Default,,0,0,0,,API in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.72,0:24:08.89,Default,,0,0,0,,But to help you out with that,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.89,0:24:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,we've actually got some sample
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.88,0:24:11.73,Default,,0,0,0,,code for you this year.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.32,0:24:13.72,Default,,0,0,0,,It's an Apple TV app.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.72,0:24:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,It's called SyncStartTV and I
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.38,0:24:19.03,Default,,0,0,0,,thought rather than just talk
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.03,0:24:20.04,Default,,0,0,0,,about it maybe I should show it.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.04,0:24:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,You-guys want to see it?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.14,0:24:21.65,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.21,0:24:22.77,Default,,0,0,0,,>> All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.24,0:24:23.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.93,0:24:26.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to switch us over
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.14,0:24:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,to the Apple TV here, if I
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.26,0:24:29.80,Default,,0,0,0,,remember which device it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.80,0:24:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,I think it's this one.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.05,0:24:33.41,Default,,0,0,0,,We've got -- I have my little --
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.85,0:24:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to demonstrate a live
Dialogue: 0,0:24:36.03,0:24:37.71,Default,,0,0,0,,synchronized stream, I first had
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.71,0:24:41.16,Default,,0,0,0,,to produce a live streaming
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.16,0:24:43.64,Default,,0,0,0,,setup and so I'll just talk a
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.64,0:24:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,little about what's going on up
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.95,0:24:45.29,Default,,0,0,0,,here.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.64,0:24:48.55,Default,,0,0,0,,I wrote a little app that takes
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.55,0:24:50.06,Default,,0,0,0,,the feed from the back camera
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.36,0:24:52.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and chops it up and actually
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.21,0:24:54.84,Default,,0,0,0,,serves it from the phone as an
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.88,0:24:55.71,Default,,0,0,0,,HLS stream.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.06,0:24:57.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And I've got two of these guys
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.24,0:24:59.60,Default,,0,0,0,,here, two phones, both sort of
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.60,0:25:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,focused on the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.63,0:25:01.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I've got my left and my right
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.27,0:25:04.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and they're actually connected
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.59,0:25:06.38,Default,,0,0,0,,over the network and they're
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.38,0:25:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,using a clock that is a pretty
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.11,0:25:10.86,Default,,0,0,0,,precise clock that's being
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.86,0:25:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,shared between them, and so they
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.80,0:25:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,are off there doing their thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.30,0:25:18.47,Default,,0,0,0,,So let me start my -- I don't
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.04,0:25:22.90,Default,,0,0,0,,have a -- I couldn't get the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.90,0:25:24.23,Default,,0,0,0,,rights to anything really
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.23,0:25:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,exciting so we're going to do
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.00,0:25:27.99,Default,,0,0,0,,this instead.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.52,0:25:29.93,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's see.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.93,0:25:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll start up my -- something
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.11,0:25:34.09,Default,,0,0,0,,going on here.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.70,0:25:37.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And let's start one of the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.21,0:25:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,cameras.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.72,0:25:39.10,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, let's get them both
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.10,0:25:39.67,Default,,0,0,0,,going here.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.67,0:25:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So you've got you.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:43.07,0:25:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Right is online.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.48,0:25:47.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And left is online.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.43,0:25:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.63,0:25:54.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Get my remote oriented
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.97,0:25:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,correctly.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:55.32,0:25:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So SyncStartTV.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.28,0:25:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,When you launch SyncStartTV it
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.50,0:25:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,gives you the opportunity to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:59.96,0:26:03.07,Default,,0,0,0,,select either left or right
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.07,0:26:03.48,Default,,0,0,0,,videos.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.48,0:26:04.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's select this guy.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.88,0:26:06.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Pops up a Bonjour picker and you
Dialogue: 0,0:26:06.64,0:26:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,can see that both of my streams
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.99,0:26:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,show up here in Bonjour.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.93,0:26:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's start with stage right
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.71,0:26:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and see what's going on over
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.50,0:26:11.74,Default,,0,0,0,,there.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:12.13,0:26:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Nothing much going on over
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.16,0:26:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,there.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.50,0:26:16.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's start this guy going in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.46,0:26:18.31,Default,,0,0,0,,sort of -- all right.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.64,0:26:19.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now select left video.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.07,0:26:24.55,Default,,0,0,0,,And look at that.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.14,0:26:27.24,Default,,0,0,0,,They're in sync!
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.52,0:26:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.06,0:26:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh my goodness.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.98,0:26:34.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Hold on a second.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.12,0:26:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.38,0:27:00.38,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.74,0:27:01.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.16,0:27:03.93,Default,,0,0,0,,How do I get my slides back?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.26,0:27:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.90,0:27:05.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.47,0:27:08.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, this is fun for all ages.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.13,0:27:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So I guess I skipped right
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.60,0:27:12.59,Default,,0,0,0,,past my slide.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:13.07,0:27:14.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh well. One of the things I
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.37,0:27:15.30,Default,,0,0,0,,wanted to mention about this
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.30,0:27:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,kind of presentation where
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.16,0:27:17.08,Default,,0,0,0,,you're showing multiple streams
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.08,0:27:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,at once is that you do have to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.74,0:27:20.91,Default,,0,0,0,,be careful to make sure one of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.91,0:27:22.08,Default,,0,0,0,,your streams doesn't sort of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.08,0:27:23.11,Default,,0,0,0,,suck down all your network
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.11,0:27:24.40,Default,,0,0,0,,bandwidth and leave the other
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.40,0:27:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,ones starved.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.08,0:27:26.27,Default,,0,0,0,,So normally you would do this by
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.27,0:27:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,throttling each stream.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.79,0:27:29.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We're giving you another tool
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.32,0:27:31.80,Default,,0,0,0,,for that this year and that is a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.80,0:27:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,resolution cap.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.24,0:27:36.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And so essentially it's as the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.54,0:27:37.77,Default,,0,0,0,,name applies, it allows you to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.77,0:27:39.38,Default,,0,0,0,,programmatically say you know
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.38,0:27:40.64,Default,,0,0,0,,what, I'm displaying this in a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.64,0:27:42.46,Default,,0,0,0,,little 480p window, there's no
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.46,0:27:44.43,Default,,0,0,0,,point in switching up the way to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.13,0:27:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,1080p.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.86,0:27:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And so when you have an app
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.98,0:27:50.24,Default,,0,0,0,,that's got video thumbnails or
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.24,0:27:51.79,Default,,0,0,0,,multi-stream or stuff like this
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.79,0:27:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and you don't want to have to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:52.59,0:27:53.73,Default,,0,0,0,,dive into the gory details of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.73,0:27:55.03,Default,,0,0,0,,your playlist and set a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.03,0:27:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,bandwidth cap, this is kind of a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.49,0:28:00.16,Default,,0,0,0,,handy thing to have.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.16,0:28:01.46,Default,,0,0,0,,There is a case where you may
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.46,0:28:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,set a max resolution is actually
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.76,0:28:05.52,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller than anything -- any of
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.52,0:28:06.76,Default,,0,0,0,,the tiers that are available.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.76,0:28:07.58,Default,,0,0,0,,In that case we'll just pick the
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.58,0:28:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,lowest one and we'll play that.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.96,0:28:12.19,Default,,0,0,0,,It's really easy to use.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.50,0:28:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,If you've got a player item you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.75,0:28:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,just set its preferred maximum
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.14,0:28:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,resolution to the CG size and in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:17.38,0:28:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,a few seconds it should take
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.59,0:28:18.91,Default,,0,0,0,,effect.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.00,0:28:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Both sort of up and down.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.10,0:28:25.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So let's talk about a few
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.03,0:28:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,other things.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.04,0:28:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Last year we introduced HLS
Dialogue: 0,0:28:29.24,0:28:30.63,Default,,0,0,0,,offline support which is the
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.63,0:28:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,ability to download your HLS
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.00,0:28:33.64,Default,,0,0,0,,streams and play them somewhere
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.64,0:28:34.61,Default,,0,0,0,,like an airplane where you don't
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.61,0:28:35.15,Default,,0,0,0,,have a network.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.49,0:28:37.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And when we talked about that we
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.28,0:28:39.56,Default,,0,0,0,,mentioned that we would be at
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.56,0:28:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,some point in the future taking
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.09,0:28:43.10,Default,,0,0,0,,a more active role in managing
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.10,0:28:43.93,Default,,0,0,0,,that disk space.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.22,0:28:46.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the future is now and so
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.43,0:28:48.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to introduce you to a
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.22,0:28:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,new part of our settings app in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.94,0:28:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,iOS 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.13,0:28:53.42,Default,,0,0,0,,This has a section where a user
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.42,0:28:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,can go and see all the apps that
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.66,0:28:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,have offline assets and how much
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.05,0:29:00.10,Default,,0,0,0,,disk space their using, and the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.10,0:29:01.50,Default,,0,0,0,,user can choose to delete them
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.50,0:29:02.84,Default,,0,0,0,,if they want to free up disk
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.84,0:29:03.28,Default,,0,0,0,,space.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.98,0:29:06.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So what this means for you folks
Dialogue: 0,0:29:06.84,0:29:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is primarily that the OS is now
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.35,0:29:15.11,Default,,0,0,0,,sort of capable of going off and
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.11,0:29:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,deleting your assets while your
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.33,0:29:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,app is not running.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.39,0:29:19.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And there can be a couple
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.67,0:29:20.51,Default,,0,0,0,,different ways that could
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.51,0:29:20.84,Default,,0,0,0,,happen.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.84,0:29:22.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The user could decide to do it
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.53,0:29:24.97,Default,,0,0,0,,themselves or we may ask the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.97,0:29:26.36,Default,,0,0,0,,user if it's okay to delete some
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.36,0:29:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,of their content if we need
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.58,0:29:29.71,Default,,0,0,0,,space for like an OS update or
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.71,0:29:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,something like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.52,0:29:32.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And so in iOS 11 we're
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.62,0:29:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,introducing a new API that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.81,0:29:36.77,Default,,0,0,0,,allows you to influence the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.77,0:29:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,choice of what assets get
Dialogue: 0,0:29:39.06,0:29:40.88,Default,,0,0,0,,deleted when, and it's called
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.19,0:29:41.27,Default,,0,0,0,,the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.27,0:29:43.27,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetDownloadStorageManager.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.89,0:29:46.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And the way it works is you
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.41,0:29:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,create a policy on each offline
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.02,0:29:50.41,Default,,0,0,0,,asset that you have on your disk
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.73,0:29:52.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and you set it with manger.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.63,0:29:55.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Right now the download storage
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.36,0:29:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,management policy has two
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.59,0:29:59.56,Default,,0,0,0,,properties, expiration date and
Dialogue: 0,0:29:59.56,0:30:00.14,Default,,0,0,0,,priority.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.14,0:30:01.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And today we define just two
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.21,0:30:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,priorities that are important to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.08,0:30:03.45,Default,,0,0,0,,default.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.45,0:30:07.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So for most people what you're
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.05,0:30:09.62,Default,,0,0,0,,going to do is mark assets the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.62,0:30:10.73,Default,,0,0,0,,user hasn't watched yet as
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.73,0:30:12.38,Default,,0,0,0,,important, and once I've watched
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.38,0:30:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,them switch them back down to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:13.36,0:30:13.83,Default,,0,0,0,,default.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.50,0:30:16.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The expiration date property is
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.07,0:30:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,there in case your asset at some
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.00,0:30:22.04,Default,,0,0,0,,point becomes no longer eligible
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.04,0:30:22.64,Default,,0,0,0,,to be played.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.64,0:30:24.16,Default,,0,0,0,,For instance, you may find that
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.16,0:30:25.65,Default,,0,0,0,,you may be in a situation where
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.94,0:30:27.39,Default,,0,0,0,,a particular show may be leaving
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.39,0:30:28.61,Default,,0,0,0,,your catalog, you no longer have
Dialogue: 0,0:30:28.61,0:30:29.28,Default,,0,0,0,,rights to stream it.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.31,0:30:30.86,Default,,0,0,0,,If that's the case you can set
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.86,0:30:32.45,Default,,0,0,0,,the expiration date and it will
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.45,0:30:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,be sort of bumped up in the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.10,0:30:35.73,Default,,0,0,0,,deletion queue.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.58,0:30:38.82,Default,,0,0,0,,So, using it is fairly straight
Dialogue: 0,0:30:38.82,0:30:39.25,Default,,0,0,0,,forward.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.35,0:30:41.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The DownloadStorageManger is the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.38,0:30:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,singleton so you go grab that.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.86,0:30:45.65,Default,,0,0,0,,You create a new mutable policy,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.65,0:30:47.36,Default,,0,0,0,,you set the attributes, and then
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.36,0:30:48.61,Default,,0,0,0,,you tell the storage manager to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.61,0:30:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,use that policy for an AVAsset
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.67,0:30:54.51,Default,,0,0,0,,at a particular file URL.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.51,0:30:56.08,Default,,0,0,0,,You can also go back and look up
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.08,0:30:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the current policy later on.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.23,0:31:01.04,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's coming your way.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:02.22,0:31:04.76,Default,,0,0,0,,The other thing about offline is
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.76,0:31:06.89,Default,,0,0,0,,that we got some feedback from
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.89,0:31:07.67,Default,,0,0,0,,some of the folks who have
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.67,0:31:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,adopted it that downloading more
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.52,0:31:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,than one rendition, like if you
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.79,0:31:14.09,Default,,0,0,0,,want your English audio but also
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.09,0:31:16.10,Default,,0,0,0,,your Spanish audio, is maybe a
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.10,0:31:17.36,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit harder than it could
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.36,0:31:19.73,Default,,0,0,0,,be primarily if your application
Dialogue: 0,0:31:19.73,0:31:21.14,Default,,0,0,0,,is subject to going to the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.14,0:31:23.24,Default,,0,0,0,,background and being quit half
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.24,0:31:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,way through, and so I'm pleased
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.08,0:31:26.47,Default,,0,0,0,,to say that in iOS 11 we're
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.47,0:31:29.21,Default,,0,0,0,,introducing a new way to batch
Dialogue: 0,0:31:29.21,0:31:30.51,Default,,0,0,0,,up your offline downloads.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.51,0:31:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It's called an
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.07,0:31:33.46,Default,,0,0,0,,AggregateAssetDownloadTask and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:33.46,0:31:35.25,Default,,0,0,0,,it allows you to, for a given
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.25,0:31:38.74,Default,,0,0,0,,asset, indicate an array of
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.74,0:31:41.51,Default,,0,0,0,,media selections like this and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:41.51,0:31:43.54,Default,,0,0,0,,then when you kick off the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:43.54,0:31:45.40,Default,,0,0,0,,download task we'll go off,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.40,0:31:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,we'll download each one, we'll
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.40,0:31:47.70,Default,,0,0,0,,give you progress as we do, and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.97,0:31:49.03,Default,,0,0,0,,then we'll let you know when the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.03,0:31:50.37,Default,,0,0,0,,whole thing is done so hopefully
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.37,0:31:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,it will make things a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:31:51.21,0:31:51.54,Default,,0,0,0,,easier.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.52,0:31:55.56,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.06,0:31:58.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. The next set of things
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.25,0:31:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to talk about here
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.10,0:32:01.55,Default,,0,0,0,,today all revolve around
Dialogue: 0,0:32:02.12,0:32:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,managing content keys on your
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.98,0:32:05.74,Default,,0,0,0,,device, and it's a fairly
Dialogue: 0,0:32:05.74,0:32:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,complicated topic and so what
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.20,0:32:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to do is hand you-guys
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.94,0:32:13.40,Default,,0,0,0,,over to our very own HLS key
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.40,0:32:15.25,Default,,0,0,0,,master, Anil Katti, and he's
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.25,0:32:16.01,Default,,0,0,0,,going to walk you through it.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.01,0:32:16.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you very much.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.52,0:32:21.50,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.20,0:32:26.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Roger.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.98,0:32:28.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Good evening everyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.09,0:32:29.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome to WWDC.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.81,0:32:34.41,Default,,0,0,0,,So two years ago we introduced
Dialogue: 0,0:32:34.41,0:32:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming, a content
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.06,0:32:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,protection technology that helps
Dialogue: 0,0:32:37.68,0:32:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,protect your HLS assets.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.61,0:32:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Since this introduction we have
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.28,0:32:44.50,Default,,0,0,0,,seen phenomenal growth.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.60,0:32:46.94,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming is used
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.94,0:32:48.85,Default,,0,0,0,,protect premium content that is
Dialogue: 0,0:32:48.85,0:32:51.30,Default,,0,0,0,,delivered on our platforms, and
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.34,0:32:54.03,Default,,0,0,0,,today we are excited to announce
Dialogue: 0,0:32:54.03,0:32:55.53,Default,,0,0,0,,a few enhancements to the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.53,0:32:56.99,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming key delivery
Dialogue: 0,0:32:56.99,0:32:59.58,Default,,0,0,0,,process that will allow you to
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.58,0:33:02.53,Default,,0,0,0,,simplify your workflow, scale
Dialogue: 0,0:33:02.53,0:33:03.38,Default,,0,0,0,,your FairPlay Streaming
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.38,0:33:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,adoption, and support new
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.59,0:33:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,content production features.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.39,0:33:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But before we talk about the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.88,0:33:12.63,Default,,0,0,0,,enhancements I would like to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:12.63,0:33:13.91,Default,,0,0,0,,start with a quick overview of
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.91,0:33:14.65,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:16.88,0:33:19.62,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming specifies how
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.62,0:33:21.61,Default,,0,0,0,,to deliver -- how to securely
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.61,0:33:23.01,Default,,0,0,0,,deliver content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:24.03,0:33:25.87,Default,,0,0,0,,There are three main elements in
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.87,0:33:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the FairPlay Streaming system,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.01,0:33:29.55,Default,,0,0,0,,your media-centric application,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.67,0:33:32.10,Default,,0,0,0,,the one that holds the playback
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.10,0:33:33.20,Default,,0,0,0,,session is at the center.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.24,0:33:36.22,Default,,0,0,0,,You have your key server on one
Dialogue: 0,0:33:36.22,0:33:38.01,Default,,0,0,0,,side that provides the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.01,0:33:40.16,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption keys, and
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.16,0:33:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,AVFoundation is on the other
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.44,0:33:43.80,Default,,0,0,0,,side that gives you support for
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.80,0:33:45.21,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption and playback of the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:45.21,0:33:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,content.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.52,0:33:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,There are five steps involved in
Dialogue: 0,0:33:49.94,0:33:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,delivering content decryption
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.07,0:33:52.77,Default,,0,0,0,,keys and it all starts when the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.77,0:33:54.68,Default,,0,0,0,,user is browsing through your
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.68,0:33:56.68,Default,,0,0,0,,app trying to pick something to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.68,0:33:59.27,Default,,0,0,0,,play, and when it does that your
Dialogue: 0,0:33:59.27,0:34:01.35,Default,,0,0,0,,app creates an asset and as
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.35,0:34:03.48,Default,,0,0,0,,AVFoundation decide to playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.00,0:34:06.33,Default,,0,0,0,,When AVFoundation receives the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.33,0:34:08.15,Default,,0,0,0,,playback request it starts
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.15,0:34:10.11,Default,,0,0,0,,passing the playlist and when it
Dialogue: 0,0:34:10.11,0:34:11.02,Default,,0,0,0,,sees that the content is
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.02,0:34:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,encrypted and uses FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.51,0:34:14.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming for key delivery asks
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.79,0:34:17.21,Default,,0,0,0,,your app for the key by sending
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.21,0:34:18.92,Default,,0,0,0,,you a key request through the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.92,0:34:19.75,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate call back.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.10,0:34:23.16,Default,,0,0,0,,At that point, you could use the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.16,0:34:24.96,Default,,0,0,0,,key request object to create
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.96,0:34:27.17,Default,,0,0,0,,what we call server playback
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.17,0:34:30.92,Default,,0,0,0,,context or SPC in short, which
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.92,0:34:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,is an encrypted data blob that
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.71,0:34:34.46,Default,,0,0,0,,contains the information your
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.50,0:34:36.81,Default,,0,0,0,,key server requires to create
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.09,0:34:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.25,0:34:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Your app then sends the content
Dialogue: 0,0:34:40.59,0:34:41.69,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption key to your key
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.69,0:34:44.77,Default,,0,0,0,,server and obtains content key
Dialogue: 0,0:34:44.77,0:34:48.21,Default,,0,0,0,,context in return, or CKC, which
Dialogue: 0,0:34:48.21,0:34:49.56,Default,,0,0,0,,is another encrypted data blob
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.00,0:34:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that contains the actual
Dialogue: 0,0:34:51.14,0:34:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.58,0:34:57.17,Default,,0,0,0,,As a last step, your application
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.17,0:35:00.71,Default,,0,0,0,,provides the CKC as a response
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.14,0:35:02.36,Default,,0,0,0,,to the key request object that
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.36,0:35:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,it initially received.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.84,0:35:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So assuming AVFoundation has
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.34,0:35:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,already loaded playlist and
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.85,0:35:11.46,Default,,0,0,0,,media data by now it now has the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.46,0:35:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming keys that it
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.02,0:35:15.31,Default,,0,0,0,,requires to decrypt the content
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.39,0:35:18.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and start the playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:18.14,0:35:20.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Well in a sense, FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.20,0:35:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming keys are similar to
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.68,0:35:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,these other resources, and in
Dialogue: 0,0:35:24.26,0:35:26.09,Default,,0,0,0,,fact if you recall, if you're
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.09,0:35:27.33,Default,,0,0,0,,using FairPlay Streaming for key
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.33,0:35:29.38,Default,,0,0,0,,delivery today FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.38,0:35:30.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming keys are delivered
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.81,0:35:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,with AVAsset accessory APIs,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.73,0:35:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,similar to other custom
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.71,0:35:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,resources, but that's pretty
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.38,0:35:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,much where the similarity ends,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.88,0:35:39.18,Default,,0,0,0,,right?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:39.18,0:35:40.46,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming keys are
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.46,0:35:42.03,Default,,0,0,0,,specialized resources that have
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.39,0:35:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,very specific operations defined
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.63,0:35:45.15,Default,,0,0,0,,on them.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.63,0:35:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll give you a couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.45,0:35:48.83,Default,,0,0,0,,examples now.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:49.06,0:35:51.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So AVFoundation allows you to
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.93,0:35:53.81,Default,,0,0,0,,free FairPlay Streaming keys so
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.81,0:35:55.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that you could save them in your
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.14,0:35:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,app storage and use them later
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.82,0:35:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,on like when the user is trying
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.87,0:36:00.52,Default,,0,0,0,,to play content offline.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:01.09,0:36:04.15,Default,,0,0,0,,And you could also define
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.15,0:36:05.69,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming keys to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.69,0:36:07.39,Default,,0,0,0,,expire after a certain duration
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.35,0:36:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and the keys have to be renewed
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.77,0:36:11.22,Default,,0,0,0,,before they expired in order to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:11.22,0:36:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,continue decryption.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.66,0:36:15.35,Default,,0,0,0,,As content production features
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.38,0:36:17.41,Default,,0,0,0,,continue to evolve, FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.41,0:36:18.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming keys will continue to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:18.84,0:36:20.69,Default,,0,0,0,,get more specialized and so does
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.69,0:36:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the key delivery process.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:22.48,0:36:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Further, FairPlay Streaming keys
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.55,0:36:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,do not have to be associated
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.26,0:36:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,with assets at the time of
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.80,0:36:30.15,Default,,0,0,0,,loading.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:30.81,0:36:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,So we think by decoupling the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.73,0:36:35.17,Default,,0,0,0,,key loading from media loading
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.17,0:36:37.18,Default,,0,0,0,,or even the playback, we'll be
Dialogue: 0,0:36:37.18,0:36:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,able to provide you more
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.34,0:36:40.15,Default,,0,0,0,,flexibility that can be
Dialogue: 0,0:36:40.15,0:36:41.49,Default,,0,0,0,,exploited to address some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.49,0:36:43.85,Default,,0,0,0,,existence pain points and also
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.99,0:36:45.66,Default,,0,0,0,,provide better user experience.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.81,0:36:48.30,Default,,0,0,0,,So with all these things in mind
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.77,0:36:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we are so glad to introduce a
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.19,0:36:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,new API that will allow you to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.12,0:36:54.95,Default,,0,0,0,,better manage and deliver
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.95,0:36:55.94,Default,,0,0,0,,content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:56.87,0:36:58.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Introducing AVContentKeySession.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.14,0:37:02.40,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession is an
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.40,0:37:03.66,Default,,0,0,0,,AVFoundation class that was
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.66,0:37:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,designed around content
Dialogue: 0,0:37:04.71,0:37:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.02,0:37:07.86,Default,,0,0,0,,It allows you to decouple key
Dialogue: 0,0:37:07.86,0:37:10.82,Default,,0,0,0,,loading from media loading or
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.82,0:37:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,even playback, for that matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.41,0:37:15.04,Default,,0,0,0,,And it also gives you a better
Dialogue: 0,0:37:15.04,0:37:17.17,Default,,0,0,0,,control over the lifecycle of
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.21,0:37:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.60,0:37:21.66,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you recall, your
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.66,0:37:24.03,Default,,0,0,0,,application loads keys only when
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.03,0:37:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,it receives a key request from
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.80,0:37:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,AVFoundation and but that -- you
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.51,0:37:32.39,Default,,0,0,0,,can change that with
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.39,0:37:33.25,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:34.09,0:37:35.75,Default,,0,0,0,,With AVContentKeySession you get
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.75,0:37:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,to decide when you would like to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.92,0:37:37.35,Default,,0,0,0,,load keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.40,0:37:39.95,Default,,0,0,0,,However, if you choose not to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.95,0:37:41.19,Default,,0,0,0,,load keys before requesting
Dialogue: 0,0:37:41.19,0:37:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,playback, AVFoundation still
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.37,0:37:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,sends you a key request on
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.04,0:37:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,demand like it does today.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.93,0:37:50.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we provide you two ways
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.63,0:37:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,to trigger the key loading
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.03,0:37:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,process.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:53.06,0:37:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,You could use -- your
Dialogue: 0,0:37:55.66,0:37:56.79,Default,,0,0,0,,application could use
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.79,0:37:58.28,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.28,0:37:59.55,Default,,0,0,0,,explicitly initiate the key
Dialogue: 0,0:37:59.55,0:38:02.71,Default,,0,0,0,,loading process, or AVFoundation
Dialogue: 0,0:38:02.71,0:38:03.66,Default,,0,0,0,,initiates the key loading
Dialogue: 0,0:38:03.66,0:38:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,process on demand when it sees
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.17,0:38:06.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the content is encrypted.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.67,0:38:09.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's see how using
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.70,0:38:11.14,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to initiate
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.14,0:38:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the key loading process could be
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.79,0:38:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,helpful.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.97,0:38:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And the first, use keys that I
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.62,0:38:16.87,Default,,0,0,0,,have for you today is around
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.21,0:38:17.92,Default,,0,0,0,,playback startup.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.16,0:38:21.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Key loading time could be a
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.97,0:38:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,significant portion of your
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.52,0:38:25.39,Default,,0,0,0,,playback startup time because
Dialogue: 0,0:38:25.73,0:38:27.52,Default,,0,0,0,,applications normally load keys
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.34,0:38:29.59,Default,,0,0,0,,when they receive an on-demand
Dialogue: 0,0:38:29.59,0:38:30.26,Default,,0,0,0,,key request.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.72,0:38:33.23,Default,,0,0,0,,You could improve the playback
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.23,0:38:34.65,Default,,0,0,0,,startup experience your user
Dialogue: 0,0:38:34.65,0:38:37.05,Default,,0,0,0,,receives if you could load keys
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.05,0:38:39.38,Default,,0,0,0,,even before the user has picked
Dialogue: 0,0:38:39.38,0:38:40.01,Default,,0,0,0,,something to play.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:41.48,0:38:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, AVContentKeySession allows
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.96,0:38:43.47,Default,,0,0,0,,you to do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.94,0:38:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So you could use
Dialogue: 0,0:38:44.94,0:38:47.05,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to initiate
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.05,0:38:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,a key loading process and then
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.02,0:38:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,use the key request that you get
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.36,0:38:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to load the keys independent of
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.85,0:38:54.62,Default,,0,0,0,,the playback session.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.98,0:38:57.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we call this key preloading
Dialogue: 0,0:38:59.14,0:39:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and after loading the keys you
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.63,0:39:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,could request a playback so
Dialogue: 0,0:39:03.05,0:39:04.29,Default,,0,0,0,,during playback you don't have
Dialogue: 0,0:39:04.29,0:39:05.30,Default,,0,0,0,,to load any keys, and the
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.30,0:39:06.71,Default,,0,0,0,,playback -- the decryption could
Dialogue: 0,0:39:06.71,0:39:07.73,Default,,0,0,0,,start immediately.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:08.90,0:39:10.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The second use case I have for
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.62,0:39:11.90,Default,,0,0,0,,you today is gaining a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.90,0:39:14.47,Default,,0,0,0,,prominence day by day and it is
Dialogue: 0,0:39:14.47,0:39:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,around live playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.28,0:39:19.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We have seen an explosion in the
Dialogue: 0,0:39:19.40,0:39:20.76,Default,,0,0,0,,amount of live content that
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.76,0:39:21.97,Default,,0,0,0,,delivered on our platforms,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.55,0:39:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,thanks to a more immersive and
Dialogue: 0,0:39:24.10,0:39:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,integrated experience users
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.72,0:39:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,receive on our devices.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.12,0:39:29.60,Default,,0,0,0,,With more users looking to
Dialogue: 0,0:39:29.60,0:39:31.37,Default,,0,0,0,,consume sports and other live
Dialogue: 0,0:39:31.37,0:39:33.77,Default,,0,0,0,,events on our devices,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.72,0:39:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,developers are using more
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.00,0:39:37.27,Default,,0,0,0,,advanced content production
Dialogue: 0,0:39:37.27,0:39:39.47,Default,,0,0,0,,features like key rotation and
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.47,0:39:41.47,Default,,0,0,0,,key renewal to add an extra
Dialogue: 0,0:39:41.47,0:39:42.39,Default,,0,0,0,,layer of protection while
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.39,0:39:43.85,Default,,0,0,0,,delivering premium live content.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.43,0:39:47.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Due to the nature of live
Dialogue: 0,0:39:47.73,0:39:50.50,Default,,0,0,0,,streaming, your keys servers get
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.50,0:39:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,bombarded with millions of key
Dialogue: 0,0:39:51.93,0:39:53.41,Default,,0,0,0,,requests all at once when the
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.41,0:39:54.67,Default,,0,0,0,,keys are being rotated or
Dialogue: 0,0:39:54.67,0:39:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,renewed.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.30,0:39:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you could use
Dialogue: 0,0:39:57.27,0:40:00.27,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to alleviate
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.27,0:40:02.69,Default,,0,0,0,,the situation by load balancing
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.69,0:40:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,key requests at the point of
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.14,0:40:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,origin.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.53,0:40:08.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me explain how you could do
Dialogue: 0,0:40:08.57,0:40:09.91,Default,,0,0,0,,this with a simple illustration
Dialogue: 0,0:40:09.91,0:40:10.16,Default,,0,0,0,,here.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:13.05,0:40:14.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider the scenario in which
Dialogue: 0,0:40:14.05,0:40:16.04,Default,,0,0,0,,millions of users are watching a
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.04,0:40:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,popular live stream like Apple's
Dialogue: 0,0:40:17.67,0:40:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Keynote.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.11,0:40:20.44,Default,,0,0,0,,It's possible that they all
Dialogue: 0,0:40:20.44,0:40:21.61,Default,,0,0,0,,started at different points in
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.61,0:40:23.89,Default,,0,0,0,,time but when it's time to renew
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.89,0:40:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,or update the key they all send
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.92,0:40:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,requests to your key server at
Dialogue: 0,0:40:27.27,0:40:28.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the exact same time.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.55,0:40:31.15,Default,,0,0,0,,That presents a huge load on the
Dialogue: 0,0:40:31.15,0:40:33.18,Default,,0,0,0,,key server for a short duration
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.18,0:40:35.25,Default,,0,0,0,,of time and then things get back
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.25,0:40:37.42,Default,,0,0,0,,to normal, until it's time to
Dialogue: 0,0:40:37.42,0:40:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,renew or update the key again,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.83,0:40:40.15,Default,,0,0,0,,right?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.48,0:40:41.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So this pattern continues
Dialogue: 0,0:40:42.63,0:40:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,leading to input load on your
Dialogue: 0,0:40:44.01,0:40:44.60,Default,,0,0,0,,key serer.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:45.65,0:40:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,You could use
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.19,0:40:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to spread
Dialogue: 0,0:40:48.86,0:40:51.61,Default,,0,0,0,,out key requests by picking like
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.61,0:40:53.35,Default,,0,0,0,,a random point within a small
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.35,0:40:55.41,Default,,0,0,0,,time window before the key
Dialogue: 0,0:40:55.41,0:40:57.76,Default,,0,0,0,,actually expires and initiating
Dialogue: 0,0:40:57.76,0:40:58.93,Default,,0,0,0,,the key loading yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:00.10,0:41:02.19,Default,,0,0,0,,So what this allows you to do is
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.32,0:41:04.62,Default,,0,0,0,,scale your live offering without
Dialogue: 0,0:41:04.68,0:41:05.77,Default,,0,0,0,,having to throw mode or
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.77,0:41:06.80,Default,,0,0,0,,[inaudible] of your key server.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:08.84,0:41:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that we have seen some
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.75,0:41:13.09,Default,,0,0,0,,use cases where initiating key
Dialogue: 0,0:41:13.09,0:41:14.23,Default,,0,0,0,,loading process with
Dialogue: 0,0:41:14.23,0:41:15.95,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession was helpful,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:16.66,0:41:17.97,Default,,0,0,0,,let's see how to do it in terms
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.97,0:41:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,of code.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:18.92,0:41:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,You could initiate a key loading
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.86,0:41:23.41,Default,,0,0,0,,process which is three lines of
Dialogue: 0,0:41:23.47,0:41:25.91,Default,,0,0,0,,code, it's that simple, and here
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.91,0:41:26.28,Default,,0,0,0,,it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:27.34,0:41:29.76,Default,,0,0,0,,So the first thing you do is
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.18,0:41:31.09,Default,,0,0,0,,create an instance of
Dialogue: 0,0:41:31.09,0:41:33.09,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession for FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.09,0:41:33.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:34.05,0:41:36.80,Default,,0,0,0,,You then set up your app as a
Dialogue: 0,0:41:36.80,0:41:37.88,Default,,0,0,0,,contentKeySession Delegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:39.13,0:41:40.70,Default,,0,0,0,,You should expect to receive all
Dialogue: 0,0:41:40.70,0:41:41.89,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate callbacks on the
Dialogue: 0,0:41:41.89,0:41:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate queue that you specify
Dialogue: 0,0:41:43.14,0:41:43.40,Default,,0,0,0,,here.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:44.06,0:41:48.08,Default,,0,0,0,,The third step is to invoke
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.08,0:41:49.71,Default,,0,0,0,,processContentKeyRequest method
Dialogue: 0,0:41:50.26,0:41:51.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and that will initiate the key
Dialogue: 0,0:41:51.59,0:41:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,loading process.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.27,0:41:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So have to note a couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:41:55.32,0:41:55.91,Default,,0,0,0,,things here.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.56,0:41:59.37,Default,,0,0,0,,There are no changes required in
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.37,0:42:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,your keys or your key server
Dialogue: 0,0:42:01.20,0:42:02.59,Default,,0,0,0,,module implementation in order
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.59,0:42:03.38,Default,,0,0,0,,to use this feature.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.61,0:42:06.11,Default,,0,0,0,,This is -- all implementation
Dialogue: 0,0:42:06.11,0:42:07.35,Default,,0,0,0,,here is on the client side which
Dialogue: 0,0:42:07.35,0:42:07.77,Default,,0,0,0,,is great.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:08.71,0:42:12.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, the identifier that you
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.60,0:42:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,specify here should match with
Dialogue: 0,0:42:15.62,0:42:17.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the identifier that you specify
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.15,0:42:19.35,Default,,0,0,0,,in your EXT-X-KEY tag in your
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.35,0:42:21.71,Default,,0,0,0,,media playlist.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.71,0:42:23.49,Default,,0,0,0,,What that allows us to do is
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.49,0:42:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,match the keys that you loaded
Dialogue: 0,0:42:25.76,0:42:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,here with the keys that you
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.40,0:42:28.57,Default,,0,0,0,,would request during playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:29.10,0:42:33.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And third, you should have an
Dialogue: 0,0:42:33.46,0:42:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,out-of-band process to obtain
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.60,0:42:38.31,Default,,0,0,0,,the keys for a particular asset
Dialogue: 0,0:42:38.69,0:42:40.57,Default,,0,0,0,,from your key server so that you
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.57,0:42:42.84,Default,,0,0,0,,could load all these keys at
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.62,0:42:45.41,Default,,0,0,0,,this point.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:45.53,0:42:46.44,Default,,0,0,0,,When you invoke
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.44,0:42:47.79,Default,,0,0,0,,processContentKeyRequest method
Dialogue: 0,0:42:47.79,0:42:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,on AVContentKeySession, we send
Dialogue: 0,0:42:50.19,0:42:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,you an AVContentKey request
Dialogue: 0,0:42:52.03,0:42:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,object through a delegate call
Dialogue: 0,0:42:54.23,0:42:56.49,Default,,0,0,0,,back, and this is exact same
Dialogue: 0,0:42:56.49,0:42:57.95,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate method that gets called
Dialogue: 0,0:42:58.16,0:42:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,even when AVFoundation initiates
Dialogue: 0,0:42:59.91,0:43:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,the key loading process.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:02.24,0:43:03.47,Default,,0,0,0,,So now you could use the key
Dialogue: 0,0:43:03.47,0:43:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,request object to do all the
Dialogue: 0,0:43:05.17,0:43:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streamings plus
Dialogue: 0,0:43:06.37,0:43:08.14,Default,,0,0,0,,[inaudible] operations like you
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.18,0:43:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,could request an SPC, this is
Dialogue: 0,0:43:10.43,0:43:12.18,Default,,0,0,0,,very similar to the way you do
Dialogue: 0,0:43:12.42,0:43:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,your request SPC with AVAsset
Dialogue: 0,0:43:13.86,0:43:15.47,Default,,0,0,0,,key sorting request.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:16.75,0:43:18.17,Default,,0,0,0,,You then send SPC to your key
Dialogue: 0,0:43:18.22,0:43:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,server, obtain the CKC and as
Dialogue: 0,0:43:21.68,0:43:23.66,Default,,0,0,0,,the last step you would create a
Dialogue: 0,0:43:23.66,0:43:26.11,Default,,0,0,0,,response object with the CKC and
Dialogue: 0,0:43:26.11,0:43:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,set that as a response the
Dialogue: 0,0:43:27.96,0:43:29.05,Default,,0,0,0,,ContentKeyRequest object.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:29.11,0:43:33.06,Default,,0,0,0,,So you have to keep a couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.06,0:43:34.53,Default,,0,0,0,,things in mind while responding
Dialogue: 0,0:43:34.53,0:43:35.40,Default,,0,0,0,,to a key request.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:36.36,0:43:38.23,Default,,0,0,0,,As soon as you set the CKC as a
Dialogue: 0,0:43:38.23,0:43:41.19,Default,,0,0,0,,response to the key request, you
Dialogue: 0,0:43:41.41,0:43:42.99,Default,,0,0,0,,would consume a secure decrypt
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.99,0:43:44.78,Default,,0,0,0,,slot on the device and there are
Dialogue: 0,0:43:44.78,0:43:46.07,Default,,0,0,0,,a limited number of those.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:47.17,0:43:48.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's okay to initiate key
Dialogue: 0,0:43:48.84,0:43:50.33,Default,,0,0,0,,loading process for any number
Dialogue: 0,0:43:50.33,0:43:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,of keys and you can obtain the
Dialogue: 0,0:43:52.36,0:43:53.63,Default,,0,0,0,,CKC's as well for all those
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.63,0:43:56.07,Default,,0,0,0,,different key requests, but be
Dialogue: 0,0:43:56.07,0:43:57.09,Default,,0,0,0,,careful with the last step.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:58.21,0:44:00.06,Default,,0,0,0,,You should set CKCs on only
Dialogue: 0,0:44:00.06,0:44:01.60,Default,,0,0,0,,those keys that you predict
Dialogue: 0,0:44:01.60,0:44:02.89,Default,,0,0,0,,might be used during playback,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.68,0:44:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and do it just before you
Dialogue: 0,0:44:04.98,0:44:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,request a playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:10.05,0:44:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So with that background, let's
Dialogue: 0,0:44:13.09,0:44:15.37,Default,,0,0,0,,shift gears and see how we could
Dialogue: 0,0:44:15.37,0:44:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,use AVContentKeySession in the
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.87,0:44:19.77,Default,,0,0,0,,context of offline HLS playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.68,0:44:24.55,Default,,0,0,0,,We introduced persistent keys
Dialogue: 0,0:44:24.55,0:44:26.16,Default,,0,0,0,,last year when we modified
Dialogue: 0,0:44:26.16,0:44:28.45,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming to protect
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.45,0:44:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,your offline HLS assets.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:31.20,0:44:32.63,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession could be
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.63,0:44:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,used to create persistent keys
Dialogue: 0,0:44:35.74,0:44:36.69,Default,,0,0,0,,as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:36.99,0:44:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Before requesting the download
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.01,0:44:43.95,Default,,0,0,0,,of HLS assets, you could use
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.95,0:44:45.94,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession to initiate
Dialogue: 0,0:44:45.94,0:44:47.72,Default,,0,0,0,,key loading process and use the
Dialogue: 0,0:44:47.72,0:44:49.65,Default,,0,0,0,,key request object to create
Dialogue: 0,0:44:49.65,0:44:50.37,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:51.52,0:44:52.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Then you could store the
Dialogue: 0,0:44:52.60,0:44:53.71,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent keys in your app
Dialogue: 0,0:44:53.71,0:44:54.87,Default,,0,0,0,,storage for future use.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:55.58,0:44:58.04,Default,,0,0,0,,With that, this will make your
Dialogue: 0,0:44:58.04,0:44:59.40,Default,,0,0,0,,workflow a little bit simpler
Dialogue: 0,0:44:59.40,0:45:00.57,Default,,0,0,0,,because now you don't have to
Dialogue: 0,0:45:00.57,0:45:02.77,Default,,0,0,0,,define the EXT-X Session keys in
Dialogue: 0,0:45:02.77,0:45:04.36,Default,,0,0,0,,your master playlist and so on,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:05.14,0:45:05.73,Default,,0,0,0,,you could just use
Dialogue: 0,0:45:05.73,0:45:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:08.98,0:45:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Further, while creating and
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.78,0:45:14.39,Default,,0,0,0,,using persistent keys, you
Dialogue: 0,0:45:14.39,0:45:16.25,Default,,0,0,0,,should work with the sub class
Dialogue: 0,0:45:16.25,0:45:18.05,Default,,0,0,0,,of AVContentKeyRequest, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.05,0:45:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,an
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.32,0:45:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPersistableContentKeyRequest.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.54,0:45:21.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll explain in terms of code
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.94,0:45:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,how to request and
Dialogue: 0,0:45:24.39,0:45:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPersistableContentKeyRequest
Dialogue: 0,0:45:25.85,0:45:28.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and also to work -- also how to
Dialogue: 0,0:45:28.02,0:45:28.69,Default,,0,0,0,,work with an
Dialogue: 0,0:45:28.69,0:45:30.03,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPersistableContentKeyRequest.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:30.59,0:45:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you recall, this is the
Dialogue: 0,0:45:33.08,0:45:34.55,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate method that gets called
Dialogue: 0,0:45:34.72,0:45:36.52,Default,,0,0,0,,when you initiate a key loading
Dialogue: 0,0:45:36.52,0:45:37.01,Default,,0,0,0,,process.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:37.45,0:45:40.64,Default,,0,0,0,,At this point, if you're trying
Dialogue: 0,0:45:40.64,0:45:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to create a persistent key you
Dialogue: 0,0:45:42.85,0:45:44.22,Default,,0,0,0,,should just respond to the key
Dialogue: 0,0:45:44.22,0:45:45.78,Default,,0,0,0,,request and request for
Dialogue: 0,0:45:46.00,0:45:47.31,Default,,0,0,0,,PersistableContentKeyRequest,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:48.21,0:45:49.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and we would send you an
Dialogue: 0,0:45:49.96,0:45:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPersistableContentKeyRequest
Dialogue: 0,0:45:51.29,0:45:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,object through a new delegate
Dialogue: 0,0:45:53.70,0:45:54.14,Default,,0,0,0,,callback.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:54.66,0:45:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,You could use
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.04,0:45:58.38,Default,,0,0,0,,AVPersistableContentKeyRequest
Dialogue: 0,0:45:58.54,0:45:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to do all your FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:45:59.72,0:46:01.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming specific operations,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:01.96,0:46:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,like create SPC, send SPC to
Dialogue: 0,0:46:04.72,0:46:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,your key server, get a CKC and
Dialogue: 0,0:46:06.88,0:46:09.41,Default,,0,0,0,,use the CKC to now create a
Dialogue: 0,0:46:09.41,0:46:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent key which you can
Dialogue: 0,0:46:11.34,0:46:13.15,Default,,0,0,0,,store in your app storage so
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.15,0:46:14.57,Default,,0,0,0,,that you could use it later when
Dialogue: 0,0:46:14.57,0:46:15.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the user is offline.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:16.70,0:46:17.73,Default,,0,0,0,,When it's time to use the
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.73,0:46:20.04,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent key, all you have to
Dialogue: 0,0:46:20.04,0:46:22.11,Default,,0,0,0,,do is create a response object
Dialogue: 0,0:46:22.11,0:46:23.20,Default,,0,0,0,,with the persistent key data
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.20,0:46:26.26,Default,,0,0,0,,blob and set that as a response
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.36,0:46:27.77,Default,,0,0,0,,on the ContentKeyRequest object.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:28.96,0:46:29.33,Default,,0,0,0,,That's it.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:31.46,0:46:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you're using FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:46:33.15,0:46:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming for key delivery today
Dialogue: 0,0:46:35.65,0:46:36.66,Default,,0,0,0,,you would have observed that
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.10,0:46:38.98,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession is designed
Dialogue: 0,0:46:38.98,0:46:40.62,Default,,0,0,0,,to work similarly to what you're
Dialogue: 0,0:46:40.62,0:46:41.63,Default,,0,0,0,,already used today,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:41.63,0:46:42.84,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetRsourceLoader API.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:43.50,0:46:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,In place of
Dialogue: 0,0:46:45.25,0:46:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetResourceLoading request,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:47.55,0:46:49.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we have AVContentKeyRequest.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:50.63,0:46:51.77,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAsset is just where the
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.77,0:46:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,delegates call apart, it's
Dialogue: 0,0:46:53.20,0:46:54.30,Default,,0,0,0,,called AVContentKeySession
Dialogue: 0,0:46:54.30,0:46:54.62,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:56.46,0:46:57.69,Default,,0,0,0,,However, that is a key
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.69,0:46:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,difference.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:58.80,0:47:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Unlike AVAssetResourceLoader,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.91,0:47:02.83,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession is not tied
Dialogue: 0,0:47:03.26,0:47:04.86,Default,,0,0,0,,to an asset at the time of
Dialogue: 0,0:47:04.93,0:47:08.94,Default,,0,0,0,,creation, so you could create an
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.94,0:47:11.72,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession at any point
Dialogue: 0,0:47:12.59,0:47:13.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and use that to load all the
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.84,0:47:16.52,Default,,0,0,0,,keys, and just before you
Dialogue: 0,0:47:16.52,0:47:18.55,Default,,0,0,0,,request playback you should add
Dialogue: 0,0:47:18.89,0:47:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,your AVasset as a content key
Dialogue: 0,0:47:21.26,0:47:21.82,Default,,0,0,0,,recipient.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:23.06,0:47:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,That will allow your AVAsset to
Dialogue: 0,0:47:25.11,0:47:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,access all the keys that you
Dialogue: 0,0:47:26.48,0:47:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,preloaded with the
Dialogue: 0,0:47:27.32,0:47:28.29,Default,,0,0,0,,ContentKeySession object.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:30.86,0:47:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we have 2 API's,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:34.18,0:47:35.33,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession and
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.33,0:47:36.52,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetResourceLoader, and you
Dialogue: 0,0:47:36.52,0:47:38.13,Default,,0,0,0,,might be wondering which API to
Dialogue: 0,0:47:38.17,0:47:39.86,Default,,0,0,0,,use for loading different types
Dialogue: 0,0:47:39.86,0:47:41.89,Default,,0,0,0,,of resources, and here's what we
Dialogue: 0,0:47:41.89,0:47:42.35,Default,,0,0,0,,recommend.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:43.49,0:47:45.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Use AVContentKeySession for
Dialogue: 0,0:47:45.74,0:47:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,loading content decryption keys,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:47.55,0:47:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and use AVAssetResourceLoader
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.76,0:47:51.13,Default,,0,0,0,,for loading everything else.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:52.12,0:47:53.51,Default,,0,0,0,,I have to point out that we are
Dialogue: 0,0:47:53.51,0:47:55.48,Default,,0,0,0,,not duplicating key handling
Dialogue: 0,0:47:55.48,0:47:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,aspects of AVAssetResourceLoader
Dialogue: 0,0:47:57.04,0:47:58.95,Default,,0,0,0,,at this point so you could
Dialogue: 0,0:47:58.95,0:47:59.99,Default,,0,0,0,,continue using
Dialogue: 0,0:47:59.99,0:48:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetResourceLoader like you
Dialogue: 0,0:48:02.06,0:48:03.33,Default,,0,0,0,,do today for loading FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:48:03.33,0:48:04.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming keys, but we highly
Dialogue: 0,0:48:04.94,0:48:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,recommend that you switch over
Dialogue: 0,0:48:07.02,0:48:09.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to AVContentKeySession for that
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.34,0:48:10.53,Default,,0,0,0,,purpose.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.66,0:48:12.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So, who is responsible for
Dialogue: 0,0:48:12.54,0:48:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,loading decryption keys if an
Dialogue: 0,0:48:14.04,0:48:15.27,Default,,0,0,0,,asset has both
Dialogue: 0,0:48:15.27,0:48:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,AVAssetResourceLoader delegate
Dialogue: 0,0:48:16.86,0:48:18.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and AVContentKeySession delegate
Dialogue: 0,0:48:18.55,0:48:19.36,Default,,0,0,0,,associated with it?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:20.69,0:48:22.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, to be consistent we
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.84,0:48:24.38,Default,,0,0,0,,enforce that all content
Dialogue: 0,0:48:24.38,0:48:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,decryption keys are loaded
Dialogue: 0,0:48:26.12,0:48:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,exclusively with
Dialogue: 0,0:48:27.63,0:48:29.12,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession delegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:30.80,0:48:32.89,Default,,0,0,0,,So your AVAssetResourceLoader
Dialogue: 0,0:48:32.89,0:48:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,delegate receives all resource
Dialogue: 0,0:48:34.38,0:48:37.06,Default,,0,0,0,,loading requests including those
Dialogue: 0,0:48:37.06,0:48:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,four content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:39.80,0:48:41.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The app is expected to just
Dialogue: 0,0:48:41.91,0:48:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,defer all the content decryption
Dialogue: 0,0:48:43.18,0:48:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,key loading by calling finish
Dialogue: 0,0:48:46.70,0:48:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,loading on the loading request
Dialogue: 0,0:48:48.74,0:48:50.51,Default,,0,0,0,,so AVFoundation could re allow
Dialogue: 0,0:48:50.51,0:48:51.55,Default,,0,0,0,,the request to the
Dialogue: 0,0:48:51.55,0:48:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession delegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:53.23,0:48:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me show you how to do that
Dialogue: 0,0:48:54.36,0:48:54.81,Default,,0,0,0,,in code.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:55.16,0:48:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It's really simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.90,0:48:58.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So here's a delegate method that
Dialogue: 0,0:48:58.29,0:49:00.27,Default,,0,0,0,,gets called when AVFoundation is
Dialogue: 0,0:49:00.27,0:49:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,trying to load a resource, and
Dialogue: 0,0:49:02.80,0:49:03.87,Default,,0,0,0,,when you see that the resource
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.87,0:49:05.30,Default,,0,0,0,,is for a content decryption key
Dialogue: 0,0:49:06.00,0:49:07.05,Default,,0,0,0,,you should just set the content
Dialogue: 0,0:49:07.05,0:49:08.70,Default,,0,0,0,,pipe to say that it's a content
Dialogue: 0,0:49:08.70,0:49:11.46,Default,,0,0,0,,key and call finish loading.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:11.95,0:49:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So at that point we will send a
Dialogue: 0,0:49:13.80,0:49:16.71,Default,,0,0,0,,new content key loading request
Dialogue: 0,0:49:16.92,0:49:18.25,Default,,0,0,0,,to AVContentKeySession delegate.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:18.71,0:49:21.37,Default,,0,0,0,,If it's any other resource you
Dialogue: 0,0:49:21.37,0:49:22.38,Default,,0,0,0,,could just continue loading the
Dialogue: 0,0:49:22.38,0:49:22.93,Default,,0,0,0,,resource here.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:23.61,0:49:26.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So I hope this whirlwind tour of
Dialogue: 0,0:49:26.97,0:49:28.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the new API provided you some
Dialogue: 0,0:49:28.51,0:49:29.78,Default,,0,0,0,,context around what you can
Dialogue: 0,0:49:29.78,0:49:30.65,Default,,0,0,0,,accomplish with
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.93,0:49:31.95,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:33.16,0:49:34.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Before I wrap up the talk I have
Dialogue: 0,0:49:34.64,0:49:37.08,Default,,0,0,0,,one more exciting feature to
Dialogue: 0,0:49:37.21,0:49:38.86,Default,,0,0,0,,share with you, and this is
Dialogue: 0,0:49:38.86,0:49:40.11,Default,,0,0,0,,available through
Dialogue: 0,0:49:40.11,0:49:40.92,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:43.34,0:49:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,We are providing double expiry
Dialogue: 0,0:49:46.38,0:49:49.60,Default,,0,0,0,,windows support for FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:49:49.60,0:49:50.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming persistent keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:51.61,0:49:52.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what does this double
Dialogue: 0,0:49:52.94,0:49:54.19,Default,,0,0,0,,expiry window thing?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:55.24,0:49:56.96,Default,,0,0,0,,If you've ever rented a movie on
Dialogue: 0,0:49:56.96,0:49:59.25,Default,,0,0,0,,iTunes you would see that you
Dialogue: 0,0:49:59.25,0:50:00.97,Default,,0,0,0,,have -- once you rent a movie
Dialogue: 0,0:50:00.97,0:50:03.41,Default,,0,0,0,,you have 30 days to watch it.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:03.67,0:50:05.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And once you start watching the
Dialogue: 0,0:50:05.29,0:50:06.84,Default,,0,0,0,,moving you have 24 hours to
Dialogue: 0,0:50:06.84,0:50:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,finish it.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:08.05,0:50:10.08,Default,,0,0,0,,We call this dual expiry window
Dialogue: 0,0:50:10.08,0:50:10.92,Default,,0,0,0,,model for rentals.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:13.12,0:50:14.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So what this feature allows you
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.94,0:50:18.29,Default,,0,0,0,,to do is define and customize
Dialogue: 0,0:50:18.78,0:50:20.97,Default,,0,0,0,,two expiry windows for FairPlay
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.97,0:50:22.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Streaming persistent keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:23.02,0:50:25.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That will allow you to support
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.30,0:50:27.88,Default,,0,0,0,,items like rental feature
Dialogue: 0,0:50:28.98,0:50:32.37,Default,,0,0,0,,without much engineering effort
Dialogue: 0,0:50:32.37,0:50:34.82,Default,,0,0,0,,on the silver side and the best
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.82,0:50:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,thing is it works on both
Dialogue: 0,0:50:36.30,0:50:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,offline and online playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:39.28,0:50:41.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So in order to use this feature,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:41.68,0:50:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,you have to first opt in by
Dialogue: 0,0:50:42.76,0:50:44.17,Default,,0,0,0,,sending suitable descriptor in
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.38,0:50:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,CKC and that will allow you to
Dialogue: 0,0:50:46.70,0:50:48.26,Default,,0,0,0,,specify two expiry windows.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:49.06,0:50:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The first one is called a
Dialogue: 0,0:50:49.92,0:50:51.72,Default,,0,0,0,,storage expiry window which
Dialogue: 0,0:50:51.72,0:50:54.10,Default,,0,0,0,,starts as soon as the persistent
Dialogue: 0,0:50:54.10,0:50:56.27,Default,,0,0,0,,key is created, and then we have
Dialogue: 0,0:50:56.27,0:50:57.93,Default,,0,0,0,,a playback expiry window which
Dialogue: 0,0:50:57.93,0:51:00.11,Default,,0,0,0,,starts when the persistent key
Dialogue: 0,0:51:00.11,0:51:01.94,Default,,0,0,0,,is used to start the playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:03.00,0:51:04.73,Default,,0,0,0,,To explain this feature better
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.73,0:51:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,let me just give you -- let me
Dialogue: 0,0:51:07.32,0:51:08.60,Default,,0,0,0,,just take you over a timeline of
Dialogue: 0,0:51:08.60,0:51:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,events and the context of
Dialogue: 0,0:51:09.77,0:51:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,offline playback.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:11.77,0:51:15.71,Default,,0,0,0,,When the user rents a movie to
Dialogue: 0,0:51:15.71,0:51:18.57,Default,,0,0,0,,play offline you would create a
Dialogue: 0,0:51:18.57,0:51:20.90,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent key with a CKC that
Dialogue: 0,0:51:20.95,0:51:22.15,Default,,0,0,0,,opts in to use this feature.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:23.59,0:51:25.23,Default,,0,0,0,,This persistent key is said to
Dialogue: 0,0:51:25.23,0:51:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,expire at the end of storage
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.13,0:51:30.25,Default,,0,0,0,,expiry window which was 30 days
Dialogue: 0,0:51:30.25,0:51:31.02,Default,,0,0,0,,from our example.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:31.57,0:51:35.74,Default,,0,0,0,,You would typically store this
Dialogue: 0,0:51:35.94,0:51:37.13,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent key in your apps
Dialogue: 0,0:51:37.13,0:51:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,storage and use it to answer a
Dialogue: 0,0:51:39.63,0:51:40.63,Default,,0,0,0,,key request later on.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:41.40,0:51:42.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Now when the user comes back
Dialogue: 0,0:51:42.68,0:51:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,within these 30 days and asks
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.80,0:51:47.08,Default,,0,0,0,,you to start play -- ask you to
Dialogue: 0,0:51:47.08,0:51:49.27,Default,,0,0,0,,play the content, you will get a
Dialogue: 0,0:51:49.27,0:51:50.83,Default,,0,0,0,,key request and you would use
Dialogue: 0,0:51:50.83,0:51:52.24,Default,,0,0,0,,this persistent key to answer
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.24,0:51:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,the key request.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:53.79,0:51:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,At that point, we will send you
Dialogue: 0,0:51:56.29,0:51:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,an updated persistent key which
Dialogue: 0,0:51:58.77,0:52:00.60,Default,,0,0,0,,is set to expire at the end of
Dialogue: 0,0:52:01.14,0:52:02.97,Default,,0,0,0,,playback experiment which was 24
Dialogue: 0,0:52:02.97,0:52:03.92,Default,,0,0,0,,hours from our example.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:05.16,0:52:06.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Along with that we'll also
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.38,0:52:08.26,Default,,0,0,0,,explicitly expire the original
Dialogue: 0,0:52:08.26,0:52:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,persistent key that you've
Dialogue: 0,0:52:09.25,0:52:11.37,Default,,0,0,0,,created, so you're expected to
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.37,0:52:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,save the updated persistent key
Dialogue: 0,0:52:13.76,0:52:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,in your app storage and use that
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.95,0:52:17.64,Default,,0,0,0,,to answer future key loading
Dialogue: 0,0:52:17.64,0:52:18.10,Default,,0,0,0,,requests.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:18.77,0:52:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,That is when the user stops and
Dialogue: 0,0:52:20.16,0:52:22.18,Default,,0,0,0,,resumes playback within the next
Dialogue: 0,0:52:22.18,0:52:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,24 hours.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:24.26,0:52:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,In terms of code this is very
Dialogue: 0,0:52:25.72,0:52:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,similar to the persistent key
Dialogue: 0,0:52:27.79,0:52:29.05,Default,,0,0,0,,workflow that we just saw a few
Dialogue: 0,0:52:29.05,0:52:31.54,Default,,0,0,0,,slides ago, however, we'll send
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.54,0:52:33.19,Default,,0,0,0,,you this new updated persistent
Dialogue: 0,0:52:33.19,0:52:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,key through a new
Dialogue: 0,0:52:35.00,0:52:36.30,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession delegate
Dialogue: 0,0:52:36.36,0:52:36.82,Default,,0,0,0,,callback.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:37.28,0:52:40.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So those were all the
Dialogue: 0,0:52:40.07,0:52:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,enhancements that we had for
Dialogue: 0,0:52:41.72,0:52:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming key delivery
Dialogue: 0,0:52:43.18,0:52:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,process this year.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:45.54,0:52:48.69,Default,,0,0,0,,In conclusion, we introduced two
Dialogue: 0,0:52:48.69,0:52:49.32,Default,,0,0,0,,new CODECS.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:49.64,0:52:52.99,Default,,0,0,0,,We introduced a [inaudible] this
Dialogue: 0,0:52:52.99,0:52:56.12,Default,,0,0,0,,year, HEVC and IMSC1.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:56.27,0:52:59.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We added the EXT-X-GAP tag that
Dialogue: 0,0:52:59.17,0:53:00.81,Default,,0,0,0,,allows you to indicate gaps in
Dialogue: 0,0:53:00.81,0:53:01.84,Default,,0,0,0,,your livestreams.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.78,0:53:05.55,Default,,0,0,0,,And now you can define and use
Dialogue: 0,0:53:06.01,0:53:09.12,Default,,0,0,0,,PHP style variables in your HLS
Dialogue: 0,0:53:09.12,0:53:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,streams.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:10.21,0:53:13.04,Default,,0,0,0,,You can now synchronize two or
Dialogue: 0,0:53:13.04,0:53:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,more HLS streams, and we
Dialogue: 0,0:53:17.02,0:53:19.90,Default,,0,0,0,,provided new APIs that will
Dialogue: 0,0:53:19.90,0:53:22.52,Default,,0,0,0,,allow you to have better control
Dialogue: 0,0:53:22.52,0:53:24.57,Default,,0,0,0,,over offline HLS assets.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:25.11,0:53:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Now there is a new API
Dialogue: 0,0:53:27.60,0:53:29.34,Default,,0,0,0,,AVContentKeySession that allows
Dialogue: 0,0:53:29.34,0:53:31.79,Default,,0,0,0,,you to get better manage and
Dialogue: 0,0:53:31.79,0:53:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,deliver content decryption keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:34.67,0:53:37.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And finally, we added dual
Dialogue: 0,0:53:37.87,0:53:39.41,Default,,0,0,0,,expiry window support for all
Dialogue: 0,0:53:39.54,0:53:40.92,Default,,0,0,0,,FairPlay Streaming persistent
Dialogue: 0,0:53:40.92,0:53:43.22,Default,,0,0,0,,keys so that will allow you to
Dialogue: 0,0:53:44.19,0:53:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,support rental model with your
Dialogue: 0,0:53:45.69,0:53:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,offline HLS assets.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:48.28,0:53:49.66,Default,,0,0,0,,It was really exciting for all
Dialogue: 0,0:53:49.66,0:53:51.32,Default,,0,0,0,,of us to work on these new
Dialogue: 0,0:53:51.32,0:53:53.51,Default,,0,0,0,,features and we look forward to
Dialogue: 0,0:53:53.51,0:53:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,the adoption.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:55.52,0:53:56.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks a lot for attending this
Dialogue: 0,0:53:56.96,0:53:57.37,Default,,0,0,0,,session.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.05,0:54:00.05,Default,,0,0,0,,You can get more information by
Dialogue: 0,0:54:00.05,0:54:01.67,Default,,0,0,0,,visiting our session page on the
Dialogue: 0,0:54:01.67,0:54:02.43,Default,,0,0,0,,developer site.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:03.15,0:54:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,You can also download all the
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.00,0:54:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,sample code for different things
Dialogue: 0,0:54:07.42,0:54:08.89,Default,,0,0,0,,that we covered during this
Dialogue: 0,0:54:08.89,0:54:09.15,Default,,0,0,0,,talk.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.88,0:54:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We have a bunch of related
Dialogue: 0,0:54:12.77,0:54:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,sessions for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:14.10,0:54:16.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I strongly recommend watching
Dialogue: 0,0:54:16.43,0:54:18.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Error Handling Best Practices,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:18.36,0:54:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and Authoring Update for HLS.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:20.74,0:54:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,These are available as on-demand
Dialogue: 0,0:54:22.43,0:54:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,videos and your WWDC app, and if
Dialogue: 0,0:54:25.11,0:54:26.68,Default,,0,0,0,,you miss any of the other live
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.68,0:54:28.27,Default,,0,0,0,,sessions you could always go to
Dialogue: 0,0:54:28.27,0:54:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,your WWDC app to watch them
Dialogue: 0,0:54:32.26,0:54:34.94,Default,,0,0,0,,offline or watch them on demand.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:35.65,0:54:36.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you so much.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:36.77,0:54:38.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Have a great rest of the week.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:38.27,0:54:38.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Good night.
